{"title_page": "Electric Castle Live and Other Tales", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Electric Castle Live and Other Tales\n| type       = live\n| artist     = [[Ayreon]]\n| cover      = Electric Castle Live.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = March 27, 2020\n| recorded   = September 13-15, 2019\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Progressive metal]], [[progressive rock]], [[rock opera]]\n| length     = 2:26:39\n| label      = [[Mascot Label Group]] / Music Theories\n| producer   = [[Arjen Anthony Lucassen]]\n| chronology = [[Ayreon]] live\n| prev_title = [[Ayreon Universe \u2013 The Best of Ayreon Live]]\n| prev_year  = 2018\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n'''''Electric Castle Live and Other Tales''''' is a [[live album]] and DVD/Blu-ray by [[Arjen Anthony Lucassen]]'s [[progressive rock]]/[[progressive metal|metal]] [[rock opera]] project [[Ayreon]], that was released on March 27, 2020.<ref name=\"LouderReleaseElectric\">{{cite web |last=Munro |first=Scott|title=Ayreon to release Electric Castle Live And Other Tales |url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/ayreon-to-release-electric-castle-live-and-other-tales |work=[[Metal Hammer|Louder]] |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref> It is a live version of the 1998 studio album ''[[Into the Electric Castle]]'', performed as an actual rock opera, complete with [[mise-en-sc\u00e8ne]]; it is a recording of one of four live performances between September 13 and 15, 2019 in [[Tilburg]], to celebrate the original album's 20th anniversary in a way similar to ''[[The Theater Equation]]''.\n\nLucassen and fellow singers [[Anneke van Giersbergen]], [[Damian Wilson]], [[Edward Reekers]], Edwin Balogh, [[Fish (singer)|Fish]], and George Oosthoek returned to reprise their roles from the original album, alongside drummer [[Ed Warby]] and flutist [[Thijs van Leer]].<ref name=\"LiveSeptember2019\">{{cite web|title=Ayreon Electric Castle Live in September 2019 |url=https://www.arjenlucassen.com/content/itec-live-2019-announced/ |work=Ayreon|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref> New additions include [[Simone Simons]] of [[Epica (band)|Epica]], [[Marcela Bovio]] of [[Mayan (band)|Mayan]], and [[Mark Jansen]] of both Epica and Mayan, with actor [[John de Lancie]] acting as narrator. The performance of the album was followed by a selection of songs from other Lucassen projects.\n\n== Background and recording ==\nAfter positive reactions to the [[Ayreon Universe \u2013 The Best of Ayreon Live|Ayreon Universe]] shows, Lucassen decided to supervise a live version of ''[[Into the Electric Castle]]'' in a style similar to ''[[The Theater Equation]]'', to celebrate the album's 20th anniversary.<ref name=\"LouderReleaseElectric\"/>\n\nThe four ''Electric Castle Live and Other Tales'' shows were performed between September 13 and 15 of 2019 (with two performances on the last day) in [[Tilburg]]; unlike ''The Theater Equation'', which was performed as an unofficial series of shows titled ''Ayreon's The Human Equation Theater Experience'' with the recording being later released as an official Ayreon release, ''Electric Castle Live and Other Tales'' was performed as a series of official Ayreon shows. Singers [[Anneke van Giersbergen]], [[Damian Wilson]], [[Edward Reekers]], Edwin Balogh, [[Fish (singer)|Fish]], and George Oosthoek returned to reprise their roles from the original album, alongside drummer [[Ed Warby]] and flutist Thijs van Leer; Lucassen also reprised his role as the Hippie, unlike in ''The Theater Equation'', in which had had been replaced by Jermain \"Wudstik\" van der Bog and only made a small appearance at the end.<ref name=\"LiveSeptember2019\">{{cite web|title=Ayreon Electric Castle Live in September 2019 |url=https://www.arjenlucassen.com/content/itec-live-2019-announced/ |work=Ayreon|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref> New additions include [[Simone Simons]] of [[Epica (band)|Epica]], [[Marcela Bovio]] of [[Mayan (band)|Mayan]], and [[Mark Jansen]] of both Epica and Mayan, with actor [[John de Lancie]] acting as narrator.<ref name=\"LiveSeptember2019\"/><ref name=\"AyreonLive2019\">{{cite web|title=AYREON LIVE 2019|url=https://www.arjenlucassen.com/live/|accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref> Actor [[John de Lancie]], of whom Lucassen was a long-time fan due to De Lancie's role as [[Q (Star Trek)|Q]] in ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'', was announced on October 8, 2018 as the playing the role of \"The Voice\" in the last performances, replacing [[Peter Daltrey]] from the original album.<ref name=\"NarratorRevealed\">{{cite web|title=Ayreon - Narrator Revealed! |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GO5yvFKISA4 |date=October 8, 2018 |accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter performing the album in its entirety, the cast performed several songs from other Lucassen projects: \"Shores of India\" from the album ''[[The Diary (The Gentle Storm album)|The Diary]]'' by his band [[The Gentle Storm]] with Van Giersbergen, \"Ashes\" from the album ''[[Fate of a Dreamer]]'' by his former project Ambeon, \"[[Out in the Real World]]\" from ''[[Embrace the Storm]]'' by his former band [[Stream of Passion]] with Bovio and her husband [[Johan van Stratum]] (who performs bass on the live album), \"Pink Beatles in a Purple Zeppelin\" from his solo album ''[[Lost in the New Real]]'', and \"Songs of the Ocean\" from ''[[Space Metal (Star One)|Space Metal]]'' by his project [[Star One (band)|Star One]] with Wilson; they also performed a cover of [[Kayleigh]]\", a song by [[Marillion]] from Fish's time with the band.<ref name=\"MascotTracklist\">{{cite web|title=Electric Castle Live and Other Tales (Blu-Ray) - Ayreon |url=https://www.mascotlabelgroup.com/ayreon-electric-castle-live-and-other-tales-bluray.html |work=[[Mascot Label Group]] |accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe album was available to pre-order in five editions: the Super Deluxe Wooden Box Set for \u20ac159,00, limited to 1500 copies worldwide, the 5-disc Earbook for \u20ac49,99, the Gold Vinyl Edition for \u20ac27,99 the 2CD + DVD edition for \u20ac17,99, and the Blu-Ray for \u20ac17,99; the Gold Vinyl Edition does not contain the tracks \"Robby Valentine (piano solo)\", \"Kayleigh\", and \"Speech by Arjen & Joost\".<ref name=\"Editions\">{{cite web|last=Cylinder |first=The Master |title=Ayreon Electric Castle Live in September 2019 |url=https://www.arjenlucassen.com/content/itec-live-2019-announced/ |work=Lucassen official website|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt also features a [[documentary]] chronicling the making of the shows and the events behind-the-scenes of the show themselves.<ref name=\"MascotTracklist\"/>\n\n== Track listing<ref>https://ayreon.bandcamp.com/album/electric-castle-live-and-other-tales</ref> ==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing     = [[Arjen Anthony Lucassen]], with [[Fish (singer)|Fish]] and [[Anneke van Giersbergen]] writing some lyrics for their respective characters, and [[Peter Daltrey]] and Jay van Feggelen writing some lyrics for the Voice and the Barbarian respectively\n| title1          = Welcome to the New Dimension\n| length1         = 3:10\n| title2          = Isis and Osiris\n| length2         = 10:51\n| title3          = Amazing Flight\n| length3         = 8:26\n| title4          = Time Beyond Time\n| length4         = 6:30\n| title5          = The Decision Tree\n| length5         = 5:44\n| title6          = Tunnel of Light\n| length6         = 4:29\n| title7          = Across the Rainbow Bridge\n| length7         = 6:05\n| title8          = The Garden of Emotions\n| length8         = 9:00\n| title9          = Valley of the Queens\n| length9         = 4:18\n| title10         = The Castle Hall\n| length10        = 5:45\n| title11         = Tower of hope\n| length11        = 5:32\n| title12         = Cosmic Fusion\n| length12        = 6:53\n| title13         = Robby Valentine\n| length13        = 4:52\n| title14         = The Mirror Maze\n| length14        = 6:52\n| title15         = Evil Devoution\n| length15        = 5:00\n| title16         = The Two Gates\n| length16        = 6:54\n| title17         = Forever of the Stars\n| length17        = 1:39\n| title18         = Another Time, Another Space\n| length18        = 6:18\n| title19         = [[The Diary (The Gentle Storm album)|Shores of India]]\n| length19        = 5:23\n| title20         = [[Fate of a Dreamer|Ashes]]\n| length20        = 5:06\n| title21         = [[Out in the Real World]]\n| length21        = 4:01\n| title22         = [[On This Perfect Day|Twisted Coil]]\n| length22        = 9:18\n| title23         = [[Kayleigh]]\n| length23        = 4:14\n| title24         = [[Lost in the New Real|Pink Beatles in a Purple Zeppelin]]\n| length24        = 4:36\n| title25         = [[Space Metal (Star One album)|Songs of the Ocean]]\n| length25        = 5:43\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break|width=40%}}\n; Vocalists\n* Edwin Balogh&nbsp;\u2013 Roman<ref name=\"LiveSeptember2019\"/>\n* [[Fish (singer)|Fish]] (ex-[[Marillion]])&nbsp;\u2013 Highlander\n* [[Anneke van Giersbergen]] ([[The Gentle Storm]], [[VUUR]], ex-[[The Gathering (band)|The Gathering]])&nbsp;\u2013 Egyptian\n* [[Arjen Anthony Lucassen]]&nbsp;\u2013 Hippie\n* [[Edward Reekers]] (ex-[[Kayak (band)|Kayak]])&nbsp;\u2013 Futureman\n* [[Damian Wilson]] ([[Headspace (band)|Headspace]], [[Maiden uniteD]], ex-[[Threshold (band)|Threshold]])&nbsp;\u2013 Knight\n* George Oosthoek&nbsp;\u2013 Death\n* [[John de Lancie]]&nbsp;\u2013 Forever of the Stars\n* [[Simone Simons]]<ref name=\"AyreonLive2019\"/>&nbsp;\u2013 Indian\n* [[Mark Jansen]]\n* [[Marcela Bovio]]\n* John Jaycee Cuijpers&nbsp;\u2013 Barbarian\n{{col-break}}\n; Production\n* Arjen Anthony Lucassen&nbsp;\u2013 producing, [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n\n; Instrumentalists\n* [[Ed Warby]]&nbsp;\u2013 drums\n* Marcel Singor ([[Kayak (band)|Kayak]])&nbsp;\u2013 [[lead guitar]]\n* Ferry Duijsens (VUUR)&nbsp;\u2013 [[guitar]]\n* Bob Wijtsma ([[Ex Libris (band)|Ex Libris]])&nbsp;\u2013 guitar\n* [[Johan van Stratum]] (VUUR, ex-Stream of Passion)&nbsp;\u2013 [[Bass guitar|bass]]\n* Joost van den Broek (ex-[[After Forever]])&nbsp;\u2013 [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n* Ben Mathot&nbsp;\u2013 [[violin]]\n* Jurriaan Westerveld&nbsp;\u2013 [[Cello]]\n* [[Thijs van Leer]] ([[Focus (band)|Focus]])&nbsp;\u2013 flute on \"Amazing Flight, III. Flying Colours\", \"Time Beyond Time\", \"Valley of the Queens\", and \"The Castle Hall\"\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|Germany4|14|id=404988|artist=Ayreon|album=Electric Castle Live and Other Tales|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 3, 2020|note=<ref>https://www.offiziellecharts.de/suche?artist_search=Ayreon&do_search=do</ref>}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Arjen Anthony Lucassen}}\n\n[[Category:Science fiction concept albums]]\n[[Category:1998 albums]]\n[[Category:Ayreon albums]]\n[[Category:Rock operas]]\n[[Category:Transmission (record label) albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Electric Castle Live and Other Tales\n| type       = live\n| artist     = [[Ayreon]]\n| cover      = Electric Castle Live.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = March 27, 2020\n| recorded   = September 13-15, 2019\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Progressive metal]], [[progressive rock]], [[rock opera]]\n| length     = 2:26:39\n| label      = [[Mascot Label Group]] / Music Theories\n| producer   = [[Arjen Anthony Lucassen]]\n| chronology = [[Ayreon]] live\n| prev_title = [[Ayreon Universe \u2013 The Best of Ayreon Live]]\n| prev_year  = 2018\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n'''''Electric Castle Live and Other Tales''''' is a [[live album]] and DVD/Blu-ray by [[Arjen Anthony Lucassen]]'s [[progressive rock]]/[[progressive metal|metal]] [[rock opera]] project [[Ayreon]], that was released on March 27, 2020.<ref name=\"LouderReleaseElectric\">{{cite web |last=Munro |first=Scott|title=Ayreon to release Electric Castle Live And Other Tales |url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/ayreon-to-release-electric-castle-live-and-other-tales |work=[[Metal Hammer|Louder]] |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref> It is a live version of the 1998 studio album ''[[Into the Electric Castle]]'', performed as an actual rock opera, complete with [[mise-en-sc\u00e8ne]]; it is a recording of one of four live performances between September 13 and 15, 2019 in [[Tilburg]], to celebrate the original album's 20th anniversary in a way similar to ''[[The Theater Equation]]''.\n\nLucassen and fellow singers [[Anneke van Giersbergen]], [[Damian Wilson]], [[Edward Reekers]], Edwin Balogh, [[Fish (singer)|Fish]], and George Oosthoek returned to reprise their roles from the original album, alongside drummer [[Ed Warby]] and flutist [[Thijs van Leer]].<ref name=\"LiveSeptember2019\">{{cite web|title=Ayreon Electric Castle Live in September 2019 |url=https://www.arjenlucassen.com/content/itec-live-2019-announced/ |work=Ayreon|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref> New additions include [[Simone Simons]] of [[Epica (band)|Epica]], [[Marcela Bovio]] of [[Mayan (band)|Mayan]], and [[Mark Jansen]] of both Epica and Mayan, with actor [[John de Lancie]] acting as narrator. The performance of the album was followed by a selection of songs from other Lucassen projects.\n\n== Background and recording ==\nAfter positive reactions to the [[Ayreon Universe \u2013 The Best of Ayreon Live|Ayreon Universe]] shows, Lucassen decided to supervise a live version of ''[[Into the Electric Castle]]'' in a style similar to ''[[The Theater Equation]]'', to celebrate the album's 20th anniversary.<ref name=\"LouderReleaseElectric\"/>\n\nThe four ''Electric Castle Live and Other Tales'' shows were performed between September 13 and 15 of 2019 (with two performances on the last day) in [[Tilburg]]; unlike ''The Theater Equation'', which was performed as an unofficial series of shows titled ''Ayreon's The Human Equation Theater Experience'' with the recording being later released as an official Ayreon release, ''Electric Castle Live and Other Tales'' was performed as a series of official Ayreon shows. Singers [[Anneke van Giersbergen]], [[Damian Wilson]], [[Edward Reekers]], Edwin Balogh, [[Fish (singer)|Fish]], and George Oosthoek returned to reprise their roles from the original album, alongside drummer [[Ed Warby]] and flutist Thijs van Leer; Lucassen also reprised his role as the Hippie, unlike in ''The Theater Equation'', in which had had been replaced by Jermain \"Wudstik\" van der Bog and only made a small appearance at the end.<ref name=\"LiveSeptember2019\">{{cite web|title=Ayreon Electric Castle Live in September 2019 |url=https://www.arjenlucassen.com/content/itec-live-2019-announced/ |work=Ayreon|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref> New additions include [[Simone Simons]] of [[Epica (band)|Epica]], [[Marcela Bovio]] of [[Mayan (band)|Mayan]], and [[Mark Jansen]] of both Epica and Mayan, with actor [[John de Lancie]] acting as narrator.<ref name=\"LiveSeptember2019\"/><ref name=\"AyreonLive2019\">{{cite web|title=AYREON LIVE 2019|url=https://www.arjenlucassen.com/live/|accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref> Actor [[John de Lancie]], of whom Lucassen was a long-time fan due to De Lancie's role as [[Q (Star Trek)|Q]] in ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'', was announced on October 8, 2018 as the playing the role of \"The Voice\" in the last performances, replacing [[Peter Daltrey]] from the original album.<ref name=\"NarratorRevealed\">{{cite web|title=Ayreon - Narrator Revealed! |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GO5yvFKISA4 |date=October 8, 2018 |accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter performing the album in its entirety, the cast performed several songs from other Lucassen projects: \"Shores of India\" from the album ''[[The Diary (The Gentle Storm album)|The Diary]]'' by his band [[The Gentle Storm]] with Van Giersbergen, \"Ashes\" from the album ''[[Fate of a Dreamer]]'' by his former project Ambeon, \"[[Out in the Real World]]\" from ''[[Embrace the Storm]]'' by his former band [[Stream of Passion]] with Bovio and her husband [[Johan van Stratum]] (who performs bass on the live album), \"Pink Beatles in a Purple Zeppelin\" from his solo album ''[[Lost in the New Real]]'', and \"Songs of the Ocean\" from ''[[Space Metal (Star One)|Space Metal]]'' by his project [[Star One (band)|Star One]] with Wilson; they also performed a cover of [[Kayleigh]]\", a song by [[Marillion]] from Fish's time with the band.<ref name=\"MascotTracklist\">{{cite web|title=Electric Castle Live and Other Tales (Blu-Ray) - Ayreon |url=https://www.mascotlabelgroup.com/ayreon-electric-castle-live-and-other-tales-bluray.html |work=[[Mascot Label Group]] |accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe album was available to pre-order in five editions: the Super Deluxe Wooden Box Set for \u20ac159,00, limited to 1500 copies worldwide, the 5-disc Earbook for \u20ac49,99, the Gold Vinyl Edition for \u20ac27,99 the 2CD + DVD edition for \u20ac17,99, and the Blu-Ray for \u20ac17,99; the Gold Vinyl Edition does not contain the tracks \"Robby Valentine (piano solo)\", \"Kayleigh\", and \"Speech by Arjen & Joost\".<ref name=\"Editions\">{{cite web|last=Cylinder |first=The Master |title=Ayreon Electric Castle Live in September 2019 |url=https://www.arjenlucassen.com/content/itec-live-2019-announced/ |work=Lucassen official website|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt also features a [[documentary]] chronicling the making of the shows and the events behind-the-scenes of the show themselves.<ref name=\"MascotTracklist\"/>\n\n== Track listing<ref>https://ayreon.bandcamp.com/album/electric-castle-live-and-other-tales</ref> ==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing     = [[Arjen Anthony Lucassen]], with [[Fish (singer)|Fish]] and [[Anneke van Giersbergen]] writing some lyrics for their respective characters, and [[Peter Daltrey]] and Jay van Feggelen writing some lyrics for the Voice and the Barbarian respectively\n| title1          = Welcome to the New Dimension\n| length1         = 3:10\n| title2          = Isis and Osiris\n| length2         = 10:51\n| title3          = Amazing Flight\n| length3         = 8:26\n| title4          = Time Beyond Time\n| length4         = 6:30\n| title5          = The Decision Tree\n| length5         = 5:44\n| title6          = Tunnel of Light\n| length6         = 4:29\n| title7          = Across the Rainbow Bridge\n| length7         = 6:05\n| title8          = The Garden of Emotions\n| length8         = 9:00\n| title9          = Valley of the Queens\n| length9         = 4:18\n| title10         = The Castle Hall\n| length10        = 5:45\n| title11         = Tower of hope\n| length11        = 5:32\n| title12         = Cosmic Fusion\n| length12        = 6:53\n| title13         = Robby Valentine\n| length13        = 4:52\n| title14         = The Mirror Maze\n| length14        = 6:52\n| title15         = Evil Devoution\n| length15        = 5:00\n| title16         = The Two Gates\n| length16        = 6:54\n| title17         = Forever of the Stars\n| length17        = 1:39\n| title18         = Another Time, Another Space\n| length18        = 6:18\n| title19         = [[The Diary (The Gentle Storm album)|Shores of India]]\n| length19        = 5:23\n| title20         = [[Fate of a Dreamer|Ashes]]\n| length20        = 5:06\n| title21         = [[Out in the Real World]]\n| length21        = 4:01\n| title22         = [[On This Perfect Day|Twisted Coil]]\n| length22        = 9:18\n| title23         = [[Kayleigh]]\n| length23        = 4:14\n| title24         = [[Lost in the New Real|Pink Beatles in a Purple Zeppelin]]\n| length24        = 4:36\n| title25         = [[Space Metal (Star One album)|Songs of the Ocean]]\n| length25        = 5:43\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break