affy 3.\"\n* ''\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1uCgyR0I8Yc Brought to Action!] \u2013 Battle of the Philippines [1944] is a pictorial report from all fronts of the armed forces Produced in cooperation with the U.S. Navy in 1944, \"Brought to Action!\" combines U.S. air and sea combat footage with captured Japanese footage to chronicle the crucial Battle of Leyte Gulf in October 1944, from preparatory strategy sessions through the action of the days-long battle.\n\n====Magazine and news articles====\n* {{cite magazine |last1=Reynolds |first1=Quentin |last2=Jones |first2=George E. |last3=Teatsorth |first3=Ralph |last4=Morris |first4=Frank D. |date=13 January 1945 |title=America's Greatest Naval Battle: Report on the Second Battle of the Philippines (First of three parts) |url=https://www.unz.com/print/Colliers-1945jan13-00011/ |pages=11\u201313, 64\u201365 |magazine=Collier's}}\n* {{cite magazine |last1=Reynolds |first1=Quentin |last2=Jones |first2=George E. |last3=Teatsorth |first3=Ralph |last4=Morris |first4=Frank D. |date=20 January 1945 |title=America's Greatest Naval Battle: Report on the Second Battle of the Philippines (Second of three parts) |url=https://www.unz.com/print/Colliers-1945jan20-00018/ |pages=18\u201319, 67\u201369 |magazine=Collier's}}\n* {{cite magazine |last1=Reynolds |first1=Quentin |last2=Jones |first2=George E. |last3=Teatsorth |first3=Ralph |last4=Morris |first4=Frank D. |date=27 January 1945 |title=America's Greatest Naval Battle: Report on the Second Battle of the Philippines (Third of three parts) |url=https://www.unz.com/print/Colliers-1945jan27-00018/ |pages=18, 69\u201372 |magazine=Collier's}}\n* {{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |magazine=Popular Mechanics |title=The Battle That Won the Pacific |volume=83 |issue=2 |date=February 1945 |url={{Google books |h98DAAAAMBAJ |p=17 |keywords=The Second Battle of the Philipine Sea|plain-url=yes}} |pages=17\u201325, 150 |issn=0032-4558 |publisher=Hearst Magazines}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* [http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/AAF/USSBS/IJO/IJO-75.html United States Strategic Bombing Survey (Pacific) \u2013 Interrogations of Japanese Officials]\n* [http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/rep/Leyte/BatExp/index.html Battle Experience: Battle for Leyte Gulf] [Cominch Secret Information Bulletin No. 22]\n* [http://ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/rep/Leyte/TF-34-Leyte.html Task Force 34 Action Report: 6 October 1944 \u2013 3 November 1944 (VAdm Lee)]\n* [http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/rep/Leyte/TF-77-Leyte.html Task Force 77 Action Report: Battle of Leyte Gulf (VAdm Kinkaid)]\n* Orders of battle: [http://www.navweaps.com/index_oob/OOB_WWII_Pacific/OOB_WWII_Sibuyan_Sea.htm Sibuyan Sea], [http://www.navweaps.com/index_oob/OOB_WWII_Pacific/OOB_WWII_Surigao-Strait.htm Surigao Strait], [http://www.navweaps.com/index_oob/OOB_WWII_Pacific/OOB_WWII_Cape_Engano.htm Cape Enga\u00f1o], [http://www.navweaps.com/index_oob/OOB_WWII_Pacific/OOB_WWII_Samar.htm Samar].\n* [http://www.microworks.net/pacific/battles/leyte_gulf.htm 'Glorious Death: The Battle of Leyte Gulf'] by Tim Lanzend\u00f6rfer\n* [http://www.bosamar.com/ The Battle Off Samar \u2013 Taffy III at Leyte Gulf] by Robert Jon Cox\n* [http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/PTO/Philippines/index.html Return to the Philippines]: public domain documents from ibiblio.org\n* [http://www.militaryhistoryonline.com/wwii/articles/leytegulfrevisited.aspx The Battle for Leyte Gulf Revisited] by Irwin J. Kappes\n* [http://www.militaryhistoryonline.com/wwii/articles/japanstaoperation.aspx Japan's TA-Operation: A Blueprint for Disaster] by Irwin J. Kappes\n* [http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/events/wwii-pac/leyteglf/cvl23-l.htm 'Loss of the USS ''Princeton'' (CVL-23), 24 October 1944' \u2013 United States' Naval Historical Center]\n* {{cite web|url=http://combinedfleet.com/battles/Layte_Campaign|title=Pacific War Maps &#124; Nihon Kaigun|publisher=combinedfleet.com|accessdate=11 July 2014}}\n* [http://combinedfleet.com/atully07.htm \"USS ''Bergall'' vs IJN ''My\u014dk\u014d'': A Tale of Two Cripples\"] by A.P. Tully\n* [http://content.library.ccsu.edu/u?/VHP,5427 Oral history interview with Edward Gilbert, a member of the Army Boat Regiment during the Battle of Leyte Gulf] from the Veterans History Project at Central Connecticut State University\n\n{{Coord|10.371|N|125.356|E|source:ruwiki_type:event|format=dms|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leyte Gulf, Battle Of}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1944]]\n[[Category:1944 in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Pacific Ocean theatre of World War II]]\n[[Category:Battle of Leyte Gulf]]\n[[Category:Naval aviation operations and battles]]\n[[Category:History of Leyte (province)]]\n[[Category:History of Samar (province)]]\n[[Category:Naval battles of World War II involving Australia]]\n[[Category:Naval battles of World War II involving Japan]]\n[[Category:Naval battles of World War II involving the United States]]\n[[Category:October 1944 events]]\n[[Category:Sibuyan Sea]]\n", "name_user": "Corndog54", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Leyte_Gulf"}
{"title_page": "William Frankland (allergist)", "text_new": "{{short description|British immunologist}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = William Frankland\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]]\n| image              = File:Dr Bill Frankland.jpg\n| imagesize          =\n| caption            = William Frankland in 2006\n| birth_name         = Alfred William Frankland\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1912|3|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Battle, Sussex]], England\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|4|2|1912|3|19|df=yes}}\n| death_place        = London, England\n| death_cause        =\n| resting_place      =\n| education          = [[Rossall School]], [[Carlisle Grammar School]] and [[St. Bees School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Oxford]]\n| nationality        = British\n| occupation         = Allergist\n| years_active       =\n| spouse             =\n| children           =\n| module             = {{infobox military person|embed=yes\n|allegiance        = {{flag|Great Britain}}\n|branch            = {{army|United Kingdom}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Alfred William Frankland''' [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (19 March 1912 \u2013 2 April 2020)<ref name=\"obit\"/> was a British [[allergist]] and [[immunology|immunologist]]<ref name=Lane>{{cite journal|last=Lane|first=Richard|title=Bill Frankland: Active allergist at 101|journal=[[The Lancet]]|volume=382|issue=9894|pages=762|year=2013|pmid=23993179|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(13)61821-8}}</ref> whose achievements included the popularisation of the [[pollen count]] as a piece of weather-related information to the British public, and the prediction of increased levels of [[allergy]] to [[penicillin]]. He continued to work for a number of years after [[centenarian|turning 100]].<ref name=\"Centenary\">{{cite news|last=Hanlon|first=Michael|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/9154756/Dr-Bill-Frankland-I-got-a-call-to-treat-Saddam-for-an-allergy.html|title=Dr Bill Frankland: 'I got a call to treat Saddam for an allergy'|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=20 March 2012|accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nFrankland was born in [[Battle, East Sussex|Battle, Sussex]], England, to Rev. Henry Frankland, of [[North Yorkshire]] farming stock. At the time of his son's birth, he was curate of St Mark's, Little Common, near [[Bexhill-on-Sea]], [[East Sussex]], in later years a vicar in [[Cumberland]]. His mother, Alice (Rose), was the daughter of Henry West, a successful ironmonger of [[Barnsley]].<ref name=Hell>{{cite book|title=From Hell Island To Hay Fever: The Life of Dr Bill Frankland|author=Paul Watkins|publisher=Brown Dog Books|year=2018}}</ref><ref name=Centenary/> He was born an identical twin; his brother (the elder twin by fifteen minutes), Rev. John Ashlin Frankland, who worked in [[Sierra Leone]] in the 1950s,<ref name=Hell/><ref>Crockford's Clerical Directory, vol. 90, 1987/88, Oxford University Press, 1987, p. 194</ref> died in 1995 at age 83. They had an elder brother, Basil, who entered the fur trade in [[Canada]], and an elder sister, Ella, who died aged 22 in 1933.<ref name=Hell/><ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anaphylaxis.org.uk/about-us/honorary-president/a-life-in-allergy|title= A Life in Allergy|author=The Anaphlaxis Campaign|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> Frankland reported that the family doctor was ineffective, and this motivated him to do better himself.<ref name=Lane/> His childhood was spent in the [[Lake District]], and he attended the preparatory school at [[Rossall School]], [[Carlisle Grammar School]], then [[St Bees School]].<ref name=Centenary/><ref name=Hell/> He subsequently studied medicine at [[The Queen's College, Oxford]] and [[St Mary's Hospital Medical School]], now part of [[Imperial College London]].<ref name=Centenary/><ref name=Lane/>\n\n==Military service==\n\nFrankland spent the war years 1939\u201345 in the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]]; initially at the [[Tidworth Camp|Tidworth Medical Hospital]], he later joined the [[Royal Warwickshire Regiment]].<ref name=CT>{{cite news| url= https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2019/9-august/features/features/from-penrith-by-pony-to-saddam-s-palace| title=From Penrith by pony to Saddam\u2019s palace| last=Meyrick| first=Sarah| work=[[Church Times]]| date=9 August 2019| accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> In 1942, he was captured by the Japanese and held for three and a half years as a [[prisoner of war]] in [[Singapore]]. He would later recall: \"Medically, as a [[prisoner of war]], we saw conditions which are now unknown.\"<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/> As a POW, he was forced to provide medical assistance for Japanese troops,<ref name=Ind>{{cite news| url= https://inews.co.uk/inews-lifestyle/people/dr-bill-frankland-oldest-doctor-107-504267| title=Britain's oldest doctor, 107-year-old Bill Frankland, on his life and cheating death eight times| last=Usbourne| first=Simon| work=[[The Independent]]| date=5 April 2019| accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> which Frankland believed saved his life.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/world-asia-46786790/william-frankland-japanese-soldier-about-to-bayonet-me| title= William Frankland: Japanese soldier about to bayonet me| work=[[BBC News]]| date=7 January 2019| accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Post-war academic career==\n\nIn 1946, Frankland began full-time work in the Allergy Department of [[St Mary's Hospital, London]].<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\" /> He and his colleagues undertook a series of trials of between 25,000 and 30,000 patients,<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/> which proved that [[antihistamine]] tablets neither reduced nor increased the incidence of [[pollen]] [[asthma]]. Frankland continued to contribute articles to [[academic journals]] beyond his official retirement and then his 100th birthday.<ref name=Lane/>\n\n===Hygiene hypothesis===\n\nFrankland believed that the rise in allergies results from increased cleanliness and the levels of hygiene in modern life \u2014 the so-called [[hygiene hypothesis]]. He has said that \"We don't set off our immune system early on, we are too clean. In the former [[East Germany]] for instance, with very poor work and housing conditions, people were less allergic.\"<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===Pollen count===\n\nFrankland was keen to provide patients he saw in [[London]] with information about pollens, such as the levels of pollen on any given day, and the times of the year when levels would tend to be at their highest. [[St Mary's Hospital, London|St Mary's Hospital]] employed a botanist to assist with collecting this information, and to complement the work on pollen counts already being measured in [[Cardiff]]. Weekly London pollen counts were sent to members of the British Allergy Society from 1953 and shared publicly, via ''[[The Times]]'' and ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', from 1963.<ref name=Hekint>{{cite web| url= https://hekint.org/2019/05/20/grandfather-of-allergy-dr-bill-frankland-the-ardent-centenarian/| title= Grandfather of allergy: Dr. Bill Frankland, the ardent centenarian| last=Turner| first=John| publisher=Hektoen International| date=Spring 2019| accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Self-experimentation===\n\nFrankland was also a supporter of the idea of [[Desensitization (medicine)|desensitisation]], a technique that aims to reduce the level of immune response to [[allergens]] by repeated low doses of the substance to which the patient has an allergy. In 1955, Frankland experimented on himself by being bitten each day by the blood-sucking insect ''[[Rhodnius prolixus]]''. He was assisted in this work by the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]], which was able to supply insects that Frankland could be sure he had never previously been exposed to. The bites eventually provoked a severe [[anaphylaxis|anaphylactic reaction]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bsaci.org/LiteratureRetrieve.aspx?ID=134068&A=SearchResult&SearchID=1670263&\n|accessdate=16 April 2015|title= Dr A W (Bill) Frankland|publisher=British Society for Allergy and Clinical Immuniology}}</ref>\n\nThis research contributed to an understanding of how long injections of allergens would need to be given to achieve desensitisation. Results varied by individual, but immunity to pollen was found on average after three years. Immunity to [[venom]]-based allergens took longer, and was found on average after five years.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===Collaboration with Alexander Fleming===\n\nDuring the 1950s, Frankland served as an assistant to [[Alexander Fleming]] in the development of penicillin. The two had a daily meeting, but due to Fleming's lack of interest in clinical medicine, Frankland said that he could not recall a patient ever being discussed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.nhs.uk/about-us/blog/grandfather-of-allergy-dr-william-frankland-pollen-count-alexander-fleming-70-years-nhs |title=Grandfather of allergy, Dr William Frankland, aged 106, on popularising the pollen count, working with Alexander Fleming and spending 70 years in the NHS |publisher=[[Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust]] |date=5 July 2018 |access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Frankland and Fleming were also concerned with [[antimicrobial resistance]] to penicillin, with Frankland crediting Fleming with saying that careless prescription would inadvertently lead to \"the death of man.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://healthwnews.com/health-news/discoverer-of-penicillin-foresaw-the-threat-of-antibiotic-resistance/ |title=Discoverer of penicillin foresaw the threat of antibiotic resistance |date=3 December 2018 |access-date=2 April 2020 |website=HealthWNews.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1954, Frankland published \"[[Prophylaxis]] of summer [[Hay-fever]] and Asthma.\" The article reported the results of a trial involving 200 patients with previous histories of grass pollen sensitivity half treated with active vaccines, and half with inactive 'control' vaccines.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Frankland|first1=A. W.|last2=Augustin|first2=R.|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(54)91620-7|pmid=13164324|title=Prophylaxis of Summer Hay-Fever and Asthma|journal=The Lancet|volume=263|issue=6821|pages=1055\u20137|year=1954}}</ref>\n\nThe results suggested that the active vaccines were much more effective in reducing allergy symptoms than the controls. The study was notable for being the first in the field which used randomised, controlled methods and a standardised approach to every patient.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Keirns|first1=Carla C|editor1-last=Kroker|editor1-first=Kenton|editor2-last=Keelan|editor2-first=Jennifer|editor3-last=Muzumdar|editor3-first=Pauline|chapterurl=http://www.stonybrook.edu/bioethics/gvandallergy.pdf|chapter=Germs, vaccines, and the rise of allergy|title=Crafting Immunity: Working Histories of Clinical Immunology|year=2008|publisher=Aldershot|page=93}}</ref> The trial, along with his work on the pollen count, was one of the contributing factors to Frankland being awarded the [[European Academy of Allergy and Clinical Immunology|EAACI]] Noon Award for significant contributions to [[immunotherapy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eaaci.org/resources/grants-a-awards/awardees/1669-eaaci-noon-award-2011.html|title=Grants and Awards|publisher=EACCI|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Saddam Hussein===\n\nIn 1979 Frankland treated [[Iraq]]\u2019s then-president [[Saddam Hussein]]. Contacted to visit a VIP in [[Baghdad]] having trouble with asthma, Frankland advised Hussein this was not the case and to give up his habit of 40 cigarettes a day. Frankland said that \"To my lasting regret, I told him that was his trouble and that if he carried on, in another two years he wouldn\u2019t be head of state. I heard sometime later that he had had a disagreement with his secretary of state for health, so he took him outside and shot him. Maybe I was lucky.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/105-year-old-doctor-william-frankland-pow-camp-second-world-war-saddam-hussein-treat-a7660611.html|title=105-year-old doctor still working after surviving Second World War POW camp and treating Saddam Hussein|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=31 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Horton|first1=Helena|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/31/meet-105-year-old-doctor-still-hard-work/|title=Meet the 105-year-old doctor who is still hard at work|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nFrankland retired from his job at St Mary's Hospital at 65, but was then offered an unpaid consultancy role in the Department of Medicine at [[Guy's Hospital]]. He worked at Guy's on this basis for another twenty years on peanut [[anaphylaxis]] and [[Pediatrics|paediatric]] allergies. After retiring from Guy's he continued to participate in academic life by attending conferences and publishing articles in journals.<ref name=Lane/>\n\nIn February 2012, Frankland appeared as an expert witness in a British court. The accused had claimed that a vehicle crash in which he was involved was caused by his losing control following a [[bee sting]]. Although Frankland agreed with the defence that such a scenario was possible, he gave an opinion that delayed-response reactions to bee stings only occurred after there had been initial symptoms following the sting. In this case, there had not been such symptoms, and the accused was found guilty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/worlds-oldest-expert-witness-william-frankland/story-fnb64oi6-1226283231827|title=World's oldest expert witness William Frankland|work=The Australian|date=28 February 2012|accessdate=13 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he appeared in an episode of the [[BBC 2]] TV series ''Britain's Greatest Generation'' and as a guest on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Butcher|first=David|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/dmdnpp/britains-greatest-generation--series-1---3-the-fight-for-freedom|title=Britain's Greatest Generation: Series 1 \u2013 3. The Fight for Freedom|work=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> At the age of 103, he was the oldest ever guest on ''[[Desert Island Discs]]''.<ref name=Hekint/> In June 2015, at the age of 103, he was awarded an [[MBE]] for services to allergy research.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/the-queens-birthday-honours-2015|title=The Queen's Birthday Honours 2015|publisher=Cabinet Office|date=12 June 2015|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/jun/12/queens-birthday-honours-list-2014-mbe|title=Queen's birthday honours list 2015: MBE|agency=Press Association|date=12 June 2015|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> In July 2015 he was, at age 103, the oldest recipient of the badge of the [[Order of Mercy]].<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 7 November 2015</ref>\n\nFrankland continued to publish; at age 100 he authored \"100 years of allergen immunotherapy\",<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.4024/36FR12A.jbpc.13.02|title=100 years of allergen immunotherapy|journal=J. Biol. Phys. Chem.|volume=13|issue=2|pages=53\u201360|year=2013|last=Frankland|first=W.A.}}</ref> and most recently co-authored, \"Flight Lieutenant Peach's observations on Burning Feet Syndrome in Far Eastern Prisoners of War 1942\u201345\" in the journal ''[[QJM (journal)|QJM]]'' in 2016 (aged 104).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Roocroft|first1=N.T.|last2=Mayhew|first2=E.|last3=Parkes|first3=M.|last4=Frankland|first4=W.A.|last5=Gill|first5=G.V.|last6=Bouhassira|first6=D.|last7=Rice|first7=A. S. C.|doi=10.1093/qjmed/hcw195|pmid=28069916|title=Flight Lieutenant Peach's observations on Burning Feet Syndrome in Far Eastern Prisoners of War 1942\u201345|journal=QJM|volume=110|issue=3|pages=131\u2013139|year=2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, in an interview for his 108th birthday during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], he recounted some memories of the [[1918 flu pandemic]].<ref name=\"Evans2020\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196273/dr-bill-frankland-grandfather-allergy-celebrates/|title=Dr Bill Frankland, the grandfather of allergy, celebrates his 108th birthday {{!}} Imperial News {{!}} Imperial College London|last=|first=|date=|website=Imperial News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Frankland died on 2 April 2020 at the age of 108.<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite web |url=https://www.anaphylaxis.org.uk/2020/04/02/obituary-dr-alfred-william-frankland-mbe-honorary-president-of-the-anaphylaxis-campaign/ |title=Obituary: Dr. Alfred William Frankland MBE, Honorary President of the Anaphylaxis Campaign |date=2 April 2020 |publisher=[[Anaphylaxis Campaign]]}}</ref><ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/obituaries/2020/04/02/william-frankland-global-authority-treatment-allergies-obituary/</ref>\n\n==Involvement with professional and charitable associations==\n\n===British Society for Allergy and Clinical Immunology===\nIn 1948, Frankland was instrumental in the creation of the British Association of Allergists. The speakers at the Association's inaugural meeting included Sir [[Henry Hallett Dale|Henry Dale]], [[pharmacologist]] and chairman of the board at the [[Wellcome Trust]], and Dr. John Freeman.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/> In 1962 the Association became the British Allergy Society, and Frankland served as president between 1963 and 1966. The society became the British Society for Allergy and Clinical Immunology (BSACI) in 1973.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===International Association of Aerobiology===\nFrankland was a founding member (in 1970) and president.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===Anaphylaxis Campaign===\nFrankland was president of the [[Anaphylaxis Campaign]], the UK charity for severe allergy issues.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe William Frankland Award for Outstanding Services in the field of Clinical Allergy is awarded each year at the annual meeting of the [[British Society for Allergy & Clinical Immunology]].<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/> The allergy clinic at St Mary's Hospital is named in his honor.<ref>{{cite book|title=Allergy: The History of a Modern Malady|first=Mark|last=Jackson|location=London|publisher=Reaktion Books|year=2006|page=[https://archive.org/details/allergyhistoryof00jack/page/81 81]|isbn=978-1861893338|url=https://archive.org/details/allergyhistoryof00jack|url-access=registration|quote=Allergy unit named after Frankland}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/80032056 Imperial War Museum Interview]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frankland, William}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Mary's Hospital Medical School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of The Queen's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:British centenarians]]\n[[Category:British immunologists]]\n[[Category:British World War II prisoners of war]]\n[[Category:Burma Railway prisoners]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Battle, East Sussex]]\n[[Category:Physicians of St Mary's Hospital, London]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoners of war held by Japan]]\n[[Category:Royal Army Medical Corps officers]]\n[[Category:People from Cumberland]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British immunologist}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = William Frankland\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]]\n| image              = File:Dr Bill Frankland.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = William Frankland in 2006\n| birth_name         = Alfred William Frankland\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1912|3|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Battle, Sussex]], England\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|4|2|1912|3|19|df=yes}}\n| death_place        = London, England \n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| education          = [[Rossall School]], [[Carlisle Grammar School]] and [[St. Bees School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Oxford]]\n| nationality        = British\n| occupation         = Allergist\n| years_active       = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| module             = {{infobox military person|embed=yes\n|allegiance        = {{flag|Great Britain}}\n|branch            = {{army|United Kingdom}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Alfred William Frankland''' [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (19 March 1912 \u2013 2 April 2020)<ref name=\"obit\"/> was a British [[allergist]] and [[immunology|immunologist]]<ref name=Lane>{{cite journal|last=Lane|first=Richard|title=Bill Frankland: Active allergist at 101|journal=[[The Lancet]]|volume=382|issue=9894|pages=762|year=2013|pmid=23993179|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(13)61821-8}}</ref> whose achievements included the popularisation of the [[pollen count]] as a piece of weather-related information to the British public, and the prediction of increased levels of [[allergy]] to [[penicillin]]. He continued to work for a number of years after [[centenarian|turning 100]].<ref name=\"Centenary\">{{cite news|last=Hanlon|first=Michael|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/9154756/Dr-Bill-Frankland-I-got-a-call-to-treat-Saddam-for-an-allergy.html|title=Dr Bill Frankland: 'I got a call to treat Saddam for an allergy'|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=20 March 2012|accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nFrankland was born in [[Battle, East Sussex|Battle, Sussex]], England, to Rev. Henry Frankland, of [[North Yorkshire]] farming stock. At the time of his son's birth, he was curate of St Mark's, Little Common, near [[Bexhill-on-Sea]], [[East Sussex]], in later years a vicar in [[Cumberland]]. His mother, Alice (Rose), was the daughter of Henry West, a successful ironmonger of [[Barnsley]].<ref name=Hell>{{cite book|title=From Hell Island To Hay Fever: The Life of Dr Bill Frankland|author=Paul Watkins|publisher=Brown Dog Books|year=2018}}</ref><ref name=Centenary/> He was born an identical twin; his brother (the elder twin by fifteen minutes), Rev. John Ashlin Frankland, who worked in [[Sierra Leone]] in the 1950s,<ref name=Hell/><ref>Crockford's Clerical Directory, vol. 90, 1987/88, Oxford University Press, 1987, p. 194</ref> died in 1995 at age 83. They had an elder brother, Basil, who entered the fur trade in [[Canada]], and an elder sister, Ella, who died aged 22 in 1933.<ref name=Hell/><ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anaphylaxis.org.uk/about-us/honorary-president/a-life-in-allergy|title= A Life in Allergy|author=The Anaphlaxis Campaign|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> Frankland reported that the family doctor was ineffective, and this motivated him to do better himself.<ref name=Lane/> His childhood was spent in the [[Lake District]], and he attended the preparatory school at [[Rossall School]], [[Carlisle Grammar School]], then [[St Bees School]].<ref name=Centenary/><ref name=Hell/> He subsequently studied medicine at [[The Queen's College, Oxford]] and [[St Mary's Hospital Medical School]], now part of [[Imperial College London]].<ref name=Centenary/><ref name=Lane/>\n\n==Military service==\n\nFrankland spent the war years 1939\u201345 in the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]]; initially at the [[Tidworth Camp|Tidworth Medical Hospital]], he later joined the [[Royal Warwickshire Regiment]].<ref name=CT>{{cite news| url= https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2019/9-august/features/features/from-penrith-by-pony-to-saddam-s-palace| title=From Penrith by pony to Saddam\u2019s palace| last=Meyrick| first=Sarah| work=[[Church Times]]| date=9 August 2019| accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> In 1942, he was captured by the Japanese and held for three and a half years as a [[prisoner of war]] in [[Singapore]]. He would later recall: \"Medically, as a [[prisoner of war]], we saw conditions which are now unknown.\"<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/> As a POW, he was forced to provide medical assistance for Japanese troops,<ref name=Ind>{{cite news| url= https://inews.co.uk/inews-lifestyle/people/dr-bill-frankland-oldest-doctor-107-504267| title=Britain's oldest doctor, 107-year-old Bill Frankland, on his life and cheating death eight times| last=Usbourne| first=Simon| work=[[The Independent]]| date=5 April 2019| accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> which Frankland believed saved his life.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/world-asia-46786790/william-frankland-japanese-soldier-about-to-bayonet-me| title= William Frankland: Japanese soldier about to bayonet me| work=[[BBC News]]| date=7 January 2019| accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Post-war academic career==\n\nIn 1946, Frankland began full-time work in the Allergy Department of [[St Mary's Hospital, London]].<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\" /> He and his colleagues undertook a series of trials of between 25,000 and 30,000 patients,<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/> which proved that [[antihistamine]] tablets neither reduced nor increased the incidence of [[pollen]] [[asthma]]. Frankland continued to contribute articles to [[academic journals]] beyond his official retirement and then his 100th birthday.<ref name=Lane/>\n\n===Hygiene hypothesis===\n\nFrankland believed that the rise in allergies results from increased cleanliness and the levels of hygiene in modern life \u2014 the so-called [[hygiene hypothesis]]. He has said that \"We don't set off our immune system early on, we are too clean. In the former [[East Germany]] for instance, with very poor work and housing conditions, people were less allergic.\"<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===Pollen count===\n\nFrankland was keen to provide patients he saw in [[London]] with information about pollens, such as the levels of pollen on any given day, and the times of the year when levels would tend to be at their highest. [[St Mary's Hospital, London|St Mary's Hospital]] employed a botanist to assist with collecting this information, and to complement the work on pollen counts already being measured in [[Cardiff]]. Weekly London pollen counts were sent to members of the British Allergy Society from 1953 and shared publicly, via ''[[The Times]]'' and ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', from 1963.<ref name=Hekint>{{cite web| url= https://hekint.org/2019/05/20/grandfather-of-allergy-dr-bill-frankland-the-ardent-centenarian/| title= Grandfather of allergy: Dr. Bill Frankland, the ardent centenarian| last=Turner| first=John| publisher=Hektoen International| date=Spring 2019| accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Self-experimentation===\n\nFrankland was also a supporter of the idea of [[Desensitization (medicine)|desensitisation]], a technique that aims to reduce the level of immune response to [[allergens]] by repeated low doses of the substance to which the patient has an allergy. In 1955, Frankland experimented on himself by being bitten each day by the blood-sucking insect ''[[Rhodnius prolixus]]''. He was assisted in this work by the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]], which was able to supply insects that Frankland could be sure he had never previously been exposed to. The bites eventually provoked a severe [[anaphylaxis|anaphylactic reaction]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bsaci.org/LiteratureRetrieve.aspx?ID=134068&A=SearchResult&SearchID=1670263&\n|accessdate=16 April 2015|title= Dr A W (Bill) Frankland|publisher=British Society for Allergy and Clinical Immuniology}}</ref>\n\nThis research contributed to an understanding of how long injections of allergens would need to be given to achieve desensitisation. Results varied by individual, but immunity to pollen was found on average after three years. Immunity to [[venom]]-based allergens took longer, and was found on average after five years.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===Collaboration with Alexander Fleming===\n\nDuring the 1950s, Frankland served as an assistant to [[Alexander Fleming]] in the development of penicillin. The two had a daily meeting, but due to Fleming's lack of interest in clinical medicine, Frankland said that he could not recall a patient ever being discussed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.nhs.uk/about-us/blog/grandfather-of-allergy-dr-william-frankland-pollen-count-alexander-fleming-70-years-nhs |title=Grandfather of allergy, Dr William Frankland, aged 106, on popularising the pollen count, working with Alexander Fleming and spending 70 years in the NHS |publisher=[[Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust]] |date=5 July 2018 |access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Frankland and Fleming were also concerned with [[antimicrobial resistance]] to penicillin, with Frankland crediting Fleming with saying that careless prescription would inadvertently lead to \"the death of man.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://healthwnews.com/health-news/discoverer-of-penicillin-foresaw-the-threat-of-antibiotic-resistance/ |title=Discoverer of penicillin foresaw the threat of antibiotic resistance |date=3 December 2018 |access-date=2 April 2020 |website=HealthWNews.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1954, Frankland published \"[[Prophylaxis]] of summer [[Hay-fever]] and Asthma.\" The article reported the results of a trial involving 200 patients with previous histories of grass pollen sensitivity half treated with active vaccines, and half with inactive 'control' vaccines.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Frankland|first1=A. W.|last2=Augustin|first2=R.|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(54)91620-7|pmid=13164324|title=Prophylaxis of Summer Hay-Fever and Asthma|journal=The Lancet|volume=263|issue=6821|pages=1055\u20137|year=1954}}</ref> \n\nThe results suggested that the active vaccines were much more effective in reducing allergy symptoms than the controls. The study was notable for being the first in the field which used randomised, controlled methods and a standardised approach to every patient.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Keirns|first1=Carla C|editor1-last=Kroker|editor1-first=Kenton|editor2-last=Keelan|editor2-first=Jennifer|editor3-last=Muzumdar|editor3-first=Pauline|chapterurl=http://www.stonybrook.edu/bioethics/gvandallergy.pdf|chapter=Germs, vaccines, and the rise of allergy|title=Crafting Immunity: Working Histories of Clinical Immunology|year=2008|publisher=Aldershot|page=93}}</ref> The trial, along with his work on the pollen count, was one of the contributing factors to Frankland being awarded the [[European Academy of Allergy and Clinical Immunology|EAACI]] Noon Award for significant contributions to [[immunotherapy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eaaci.org/resources/grants-a-awards/awardees/1669-eaaci-noon-award-2011.html|title=Grants and Awards|publisher=EACCI|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Saddam Hussein===\n\nIn 1979 Frankland treated [[Iraq]]\u2019s then-president [[Saddam Hussein]]. Contacted to visit a VIP in [[Baghdad]] having trouble with asthma, Frankland advised Hussein this was not the case and to give up his habit of 40 cigarettes a day. Frankland said that \"To my lasting regret, I told him that was his trouble and that if he carried on, in another two years he wouldn\u2019t be head of state. I heard sometime later that he had had a disagreement with his secretary of state for health, so he took him outside and shot him. Maybe I was lucky.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/105-year-old-doctor-william-frankland-pow-camp-second-world-war-saddam-hussein-treat-a7660611.html|title=105-year-old doctor still working after surviving Second World War POW camp and treating Saddam Hussein|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=31 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Horton|first1=Helena|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/31/meet-105-year-old-doctor-still-hard-work/|title=Meet the 105-year-old doctor who is still hard at work|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nFrankland retired from his job at St Mary's Hospital at 65, but was then offered an unpaid consultancy role in the Department of Medicine at [[Guy's Hospital]]. He worked at Guy's on this basis for another twenty years on peanut [[anaphylaxis]] and [[Pediatrics|paediatric]] allergies. After retiring from Guy's he continued to participate in academic life by attending conferences and publishing articles in journals.<ref name=Lane/>\n\nIn February 2012, Frankland appeared as an expert witness in a British court. The accused had claimed that a vehicle crash in which he was involved was caused by his losing control following a [[bee sting]]. Although Frankland agreed with the defence that such a scenario was possible, he gave an opinion that delayed-response reactions to bee stings only occurred after there had been initial symptoms following the sting. In this case, there had not been such symptoms, and the accused was found guilty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/worlds-oldest-expert-witness-william-frankland/story-fnb64oi6-1226283231827|title=World's oldest expert witness William Frankland|work=The Australian|date=28 February 2012|accessdate=13 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he appeared in an episode of the [[BBC 2]] TV series ''Britain's Greatest Generation'' and as a guest on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Butcher|first=David|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/dmdnpp/britains-greatest-generation--series-1---3-the-fight-for-freedom|title=Britain's Greatest Generation: Series 1 \u2013 3. The Fight for Freedom|work=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> At the age of 103, he was the oldest ever guest on ''[[Desert Island Discs]]''.<ref name=Hekint/> In June 2015, at the age of 103, he was awarded an [[MBE]] for services to allergy research.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/the-queens-birthday-honours-2015|title=The Queen's Birthday Honours 2015|publisher=Cabinet Office|date=12 June 2015|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/jun/12/queens-birthday-honours-list-2014-mbe|title=Queen's birthday honours list 2015: MBE|agency=Press Association|date=12 June 2015|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> In July 2015 he was, at age 103, the oldest recipient of the badge of the [[Order of Mercy]].<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 7 November 2015</ref>\n\nFrankland continued to publish; at age 100 he authored \"100 years of allergen immunotherapy\",<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.4024/36FR12A.jbpc.13.02|title=100 years of allergen immunotherapy|journal=J. Biol. Phys. Chem.|volume=13|issue=2|pages=53\u201360|year=2013|last=Frankland|first=W.A.}}</ref> and most recently co-authored, \"Flight Lieutenant Peach's observations on Burning Feet Syndrome in Far Eastern Prisoners of War 1942\u201345\" in the journal ''[[QJM (journal)|QJM]]'' in 2016 (aged 104).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Roocroft|first1=N.T.|last2=Mayhew|first2=E.|last3=Parkes|first3=M.|last4=Frankland|first4=W.A.|last5=Gill|first5=G.V.|last6=Bouhassira|first6=D.|last7=Rice|first7=A. S. C.|doi=10.1093/qjmed/hcw195|pmid=28069916|title=Flight Lieutenant Peach's observations on Burning Feet Syndrome in Far Eastern Prisoners of War 1942\u201345|journal=QJM|volume=110|issue=3|pages=131\u2013139|year=2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, in an interview for his 108th birthday during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], he recounted some memories of the [[1918 flu pandemic]].<ref name=\"Evans2020\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196273/dr-bill-frankland-grandfather-allergy-celebrates/|title=Dr Bill Frankland, the grandfather of allergy, celebrates his 108th birthday {{!}} Imperial News {{!}} Imperial College London|last=|first=|date=|website=Imperial News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Frankland died on 2 April 2020 at the age of 108.<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite web |url=https://www.anaphylaxis.org.uk/2020/04/02/obituary-dr-alfred-william-frankland-mbe-honorary-president-of-the-anaphylaxis-campaign/ |title=Obituary: Dr. Alfred William Frankland MBE, Honorary President of the Anaphylaxis Campaign |date=2 April 2020 |publisher=[[Anaphylaxis Campaign]]}}</ref><ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/obituaries/2020/04/02/william-frankland-global-authority-treatment-allergies-obituary/</ref>\n\n==Involvement with professional and charitable associations==\n\n===British Society for Allergy and Clinical Immunology===\nIn 1948, Frankland was instrumental in the creation of the British Association of Allergists. The speakers at the Association's inaugural meeting included Sir [[Henry Hallett Dale|Henry Dale]], [[pharmacologist]] and chairman of the board at the [[Wellcome Trust]], and Dr. John Freeman.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/> In 1962 the Association became the British Allergy Society, and Frankland served as president between 1963 and 1966. The society became the British Society for Allergy and Clinical Immunology (BSACI) in 1973.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===International Association of Aerobiology===\nFrankland was a founding member (in 1970) and president.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===Anaphylaxis Campaign===\nFrankland was president of the [[Anaphylaxis Campaign]], the UK charity for severe allergy issues.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe William Frankland Award for Outstanding Services in the field of Clinical Allergy is awarded each year at the annual meeting of the [[British Society for Allergy & Clinical Immunology]].<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/> The allergy clinic at St Mary's Hospital is named in his honor.<ref>{{cite book|title=Allergy: The History of a Modern Malady|first=Mark|last=Jackson|location=London|publisher=Reaktion Books|year=2006|page=[https://archive.org/details/allergyhistoryof00jack/page/81 81]|isbn=978-1861893338|url=https://archive.org/details/allergyhistoryof00jack|url-access=registration|quote=Allergy unit named after Frankland}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/80032056 Imperial War Museum Interview]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frankland, William}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Mary's Hospital Medical School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of The Queen's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:British centenarians]]\n[[Category:British immunologists]]\n[[Category:British World War II prisoners of war]]\n[[Category:Burma Railway prisoners]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Battle, East Sussex]]\n[[Category:Physicians of St Mary's Hospital, London]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoners of war held by Japan]]\n[[Category:Royal Army Medical Corps officers]]\n[[Category:People from Cumberland]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript| Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Frankland_(allergist)"}
{"title_page": "Women park", "text_new": "Women parks are women-only amusement parks. These are sites prominent in Islamic cities. Men and boys are not allowed to enter. <ref>{{cite web |title=\u067e\u0627\u0631\u06a9 \u0628\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u061b \u0648\u0631\u0648\u062f \u0622\u0642\u0627\u06cc\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u0645\u0646\u0648\u0639 |url=https://delta.ir/mag/69694/\u067e\u0627\u0631\u06a9-\u0628\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0646/ |website=\u067e\u0627\u0645 \u062f\u0644\u062a\u0627 |publisher=9 June 2019 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=Persian}}</ref>\n==history==\nThe first women park was established in [[Helena, Montana]] in 1913, the first one in Iran was established in [[Borujerd]] in 2000s.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u067e\u0627\u0631\u06a9 \u0628\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0639\u0631\u0635\u0647\u200c\u0627\u06cc \u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u0641\u0639\u0627\u0644\u06cc\u062a \u0627\u062c\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc \u0648 \u0641\u0631\u0647\u0646\u06af\u06cc \u0632\u0646\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u062a|publisher=\u062e\u0628\u0631\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u0641\u0627\u0631\u0633 |url=https://www.farsnews.com/markazi/news/13980701000934/\u067e\u0627\u0631\u06a9-\u0628\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0646-\u0639\u0631\u0635\u0647\u200c\u0627\u06cc-\u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc-\u0641\u0639\u0627\u0644\u06cc\u062a-\u0627\u062c\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc-\u0648-\u0641\u0631\u0647\u0646\u06af\u06cc-\u0632\u0646\u0627\u0646-\u0627\u0633\u062a |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=Persian}}</ref>\n\n==by country==\n===Iran===\nIn different cities there are amusement parks where men are not allowed to enter with the aim of [[Sex segregation in Iran|sex segragtion]]. [[Masoumeh Ebtekar]] has said that establishing these parks is a national essential. These parks are in many big and small cities in the country, such as:\n* Tehran (5 women parks; namely, Behesht-e-madran, Pardis-e-Banovan, Boostan-e-Narges, Shahrbanoo Complex, Reyhane park)\n* Shiraz\n* Esfahan\n* Mashhad\n* Tabriz\n* Nowshahr\n* Bandar Abbas\n* Rasht\n* Kerman\n* Marand\n===Pakistan===\nIn 2012 a wmen park called [[Fatima Jinnah]] was established in [[Lahore]] with walls 7 feet in height. Authorities have promised to establish 10 more others.<ref>{{cite web |title=Are women-only parks the answer to street harassment in Pakistan? |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/are-women-only-parks-the-answer-to-street-harassment-in-pakistan-8223147.html |publisher=The Independent |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=23 October 2012}}</ref> \n===Saudi Arabia===\nThe first female-only trampoline park was established by Bounce in the capital of Saudi Arabia, in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=First female-only trampoline park |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1385816/corporate-news |website=Arabnews |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=11 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==refrence==\n\n\n\n[[Category:Sex segregation]]\n", "text_old": "Women parks are women-only amusement parks. These are sites prominent in Islamic cities. Men and boys are not allowed to enter. <ref>{{cite web |title=\u067e\u0627\u0631\u06a9 \u0628\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u061b \u0648\u0631\u0648\u062f \u0622\u0642\u0627\u06cc\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u0645\u0646\u0648\u0639 |url=https://delta.ir/mag/69694/\u067e\u0627\u0631\u06a9-\u0628\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0646/ |website=\u067e\u0627\u0645 \u062f\u0644\u062a\u0627 |publisher=9 June 2019 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=Persian}}</ref>\n==history==\nThe first women park was established in [[Helena, Montana]] in 1913, the first one in Iran was established in [[Borujerd]] in 2000s.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u067e\u0627\u0631\u06a9 \u0628\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0639\u0631\u0635\u0647\u200c\u0627\u06cc \u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u0641\u0639\u0627\u0644\u06cc\u062a \u0627\u062c\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc \u0648 \u0641\u0631\u0647\u0646\u06af\u06cc \u0632\u0646\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u062a| \u0646\u0627\u0634\u0631 =\u062e\u0628\u0631\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u0641\u0627\u0631\u0633 |url=https://www.farsnews.com/markazi/news/13980701000934/\u067e\u0627\u0631\u06a9-\u0628\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0646-\u0639\u0631\u0635\u0647\u200c\u0627\u06cc-\u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc-\u0641\u0639\u0627\u0644\u06cc\u062a-\u0627\u062c\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc-\u0648-\u0641\u0631\u0647\u0646\u06af\u06cc-\u0632\u0646\u0627\u0646-\u0627\u0633\u062a |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=Persian}}</ref>\n==by country==\n===Iran===\nIn different cities there are amusement parks where men are not allowed to enter with the aim of [[Sex segregation in Iran|sex segragtion]]. [[Masoumeh Ebtekar]] has said that establishing these parks is a national essential. These parks are in many big and small cities in the country, such as:\n* Tehran (5 women parks; namely, Behesht-e-madran, Pardis-e-Banovan, Boostan-e-Narges, Shahrbanoo Complex, Reyhane park)\n* Shiraz\n* Esfahan\n* Mashhad\n* Tabriz\n* Nowshahr\n* Bandar Abbas\n* Rasht\n* Kerman\n* Marand\n===Pakistan===\nIn 2012 a wmen park called [[Fatima Jinnah]] was established in [[Lahore]] with walls 7 feet in height. Authorities have promised to establish 10 more others.<ref>{{cite web |title=Are women-only parks the answer to street harassment in Pakistan? |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/are-women-only-parks-the-answer-to-street-harassment-in-pakistan-8223147.html |publisher=The Independent |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=23 October 2012}}</ref> \n===Saudi Arabia===\nThe first female-only trampoline park was established by Bounce in the capital of Saudi Arabia, in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=First female-only trampoline park |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1385816/corporate-news |website=Arabnews |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=11 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==refrence==\n\n\n\n[[Category:Sex segregation]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Women_park"}
{"title_page": "Nakasuk", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=August 2018}}\n\n'''Nakasuk''' ([[Inuktitut syllabics]]: '''\u14c7\u1472\u14f1\u1483''' {{IPA-all|nakasuk}}) was an [[Inuit|Inuk]] who was born at a [[Seal hunting|sealing]] camp near [[Pangnirtung]], [[Northwest Territories]] (now [[Nunavut]]) in the early 20th century and grew up around [[Kimmirut, Nunavut|Kimmirut]] (formerly ''Lake Harbour'').  He assisted a [[US Navy]] party wintering on [[Baffin Island]] during the 1941\u20131942 winter to find a suitable location for a US air base.  \n\nThe site they selected is the location of the modern community of [[Iqaluit]]. Nakasuk remained at the site to assist the Americans in establishing their base, and settled there permanently after its completion, becoming Iqaluit's first permanent resident. He is therefore remembered as the founder of Iqaluit, and [[Nakasuk School|Nakasuk Elementary School]]  is named in his honour.\n\nHis name means \"[[Urinary bladder|bladder]]\" in [[Inuktitut]].\n\n==External links==\n*[http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic56-1-63.pdf Crystal Two: The Origin of Iqaluit] \n* [https://archives-manuscripts.dartmouth.edu/repositories/2/resources/1019 ''Nakasuk is an Eskimo'' Manuscript] at Dartmouth College Library\n\n[[Category:Inuit from the Northwest Territories]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of World War II]]\n[[Category:City founders]]\n[[Category:People from Iqaluit]]\n[[Category:People from Pangnirtung]]\n[[Category:People from Kimmirut]]\n\n{{Canada-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=August 2018}}\n\n'''Nakasuk''' ([[Inuktitut syllabics]]: '''\u14c7\u1472\u14f1\u1483''' {{IPA-all|nakasuk}}) was an [[Inuit|Inuk]] who was born at a [[Seal hunting|sealing]] camp near [[Pangnirtung]], [[Northwest Territories]] (now [[Nunavut]]) in the early 20th century and grew up around [[Kimmirut, Nunavut|Kimmirut]] (formerly ''Lake Harbour'').  He assisted a [[US Navy]] party wintering on [[Baffin Island]] during the 1941\u20131942 winter to find a suitable location for a US air base.  \n\nThe site they selected is the location of the modern community of [[Iqaluit]]. Nakasuk remained at the site to assist the Americans in establishing their base, and settled there permanently after its completion, becoming Iqaluit's first permanent resident. He is therefore remembered as the founder of Iqaluit, and [[Nakasuk School|Nakasuk Elementary School]]  is named in his honour.\n\nHis name means \"[[Urinary bladder|bladder]]\" in [[Inuktitut]].\n\n==External links==\n*[http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic56-1-63.pdf Crystal Two: The Origin of Iqaluit] \n\n[[Category:Inuit from the Northwest Territories]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of World War II]]\n[[Category:City founders]]\n[[Category:People from Iqaluit]]\n[[Category:People from Pangnirtung]]\n[[Category:People from Kimmirut]]\n\n{{Canada-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Igrallert", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:added  link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nakasuk"}
{"title_page": "List of Brahmin dynasties and states", "text_new": "{{original research|date=April 2020}}\n{{princely states topics}}\n[[File:Main Gate of Darbhanga Fort.jpg|thumb|Main Gate of [[Darbhanga Fort]]|alt=|303x303px]]\n[[Brahmin|Brahman]]s occupy the highest ritual position among the four [[Varna (Hinduism)|Varnas]] of [[Hinduism]]. Since the Late Vedic period the Brahmins, who were generally classified as priests,mentor,teacher who were also [[Monarch|Rulers]], [[Zamindar]]s,[[King|Kings]],[[Warrior|Warriors]] and holders of other highest administrative posts.<ref name=\"Banu1992p22\">{{cite book |author=U. A. B. Razia Akter Banu |year=1992 |title=Islam in Bangladesh |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XyzqATEDPSgC&pg=PA22 |publisher=E. J. Brill |page=22 |isbn=90-04-09497-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Idea of Nation and Its Future in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6CElDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA219|page=219|author=Shibani Kinkar Chaube|publisher=Taylor & Francis|accessdate=26 October 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Between the Empires: Society in India 300 BCE to 400 CE|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=efaOR_-YsIcC|author=Patrick Olivelle|page=151|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>Due to their martial abilities, [[Brahmins|Brahmans]] were described as [[Martial race|'the oldest martial community']], in the past having two of the oldest regiments, the [[1st Brahmans]] and [[3rd Brahmans]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Gajendra|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=3cVMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA29&dq=brahmins+martial+class&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjn1pmV3eTmAhWWIbcAHe4KCTAQ6AEILTAC#v=onepage&q=brahmins%20martial%20class&f=false|title=The Testimonies of Indian Soldiers and the Two World Wars: Between Self and Sepoy|date=2014-01-16|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=978-1-78093-820-2|language=en}}</ref> [[Brahmin|Brahmans]] are recruited in Army because of their magnificent physique; their breeding and pride of race is reflected in their cleanliness and smartness on parade. They are fine athletes, expert wrestlers, and excel in feats of strength; and they have a high reputation for courage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiandefencereview.com/interviews/soldiers-the-rajput-and-brahman/|title=Soldiers: The Rajput and Brahman|website=Indian Defence Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==Brahmin Empires, Dynasties, Princely States and Zamidari Estates in Indian Subcontinent :==\nFollowing is the List of Brahmin Empires, Dynasties,Princely States and Zamidari Estates Ruled By Brahmins in the Indian Subcontinent :\n\n# The [[Shunga Empire]] of Magadha was established By [[Pushyamitra Shunga]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Major World Religions: From Their Origins to the Present|author=Lloyd V. J. Ridgeon|page=18|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TC9TlHTe0xUC|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2003}}</ref>\n# The [[Kanva dynasty|Kanva Dynasty]] replaced the [[Shunga Empire]] in Magadha and Ruled in the Eastern regions of India<ref>{{Cite book|last=Chaurasia|first=Radhey Shyam|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=cWmsQQ2smXIC&pg=PA132&dq=kanva+dynasty&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjb7OD4lszoAhU38XMBHQAjBgIQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=kanva%20dynasty&f=false|title=History of Ancient India: Earliest Times to 1000 A.D.|date=2002-05|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist|isbn=978-81-269-0027-5|language=en}}</ref>\n# The [[Satavahana Dynasty]] - 230bc to 250ad In present day part of [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Gujrat]], [[Maharashtra]],[[Telangana]], [[Rajasthan]],[[Northern Karnataka]] etc<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=bQjwBQAAQBAJ&pg=PR124&dq=satavahana+brahmins&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwig7Z25l8zoAhXk7HMBHao_BKsQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=satavahana%20brahmins&f=false|title=U.G.C.-NET/J.R.F./SET Itihaas (Paper-II & III)|publisher=Upkar Prakashan|isbn=978-93-5013-084-1|language=hi}}</ref>\n# [[Parivrajaka dynasty|Parivrajaka Dynasty]] Ruled parts of Central India during the 5th and 6th centuries. The kings of this Dynasty bore the title Maharaja, and probably Ruled as feudatories of the [[Gupta Empire]]. The royal Family came from a Lineage of Brahmins of [[Bharadwaja|Bharadwaj Gotra]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Goyal|first=Shankar|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=mCcwAQAAIAAJ&q=Parivrajaka+Dynasty+brahmin&dq=Parivrajaka+Dynasty+brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjLqujal8zoAhUF73MBHY2dACcQ6AEIJzAA|title=India's ancient past|date=2004-01-01|publisher=Book Enclave|language=en}}</ref>\n# [[Kadamba dynasty|Kadamba Dynasty]] (345 \u2013 525 CE) was a Dynasty that Ruled [[North Karnataka|Northern Karnataka]] and the [[Konkan]] from [[Banavasi]] in present-day [[Uttara Kannada]] district<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pruthi|first=R. K.|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=rC1bJcd-MDUC&pg=PA228&dq=Kadamba+Dynasty+brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6-OqdmMzoAhXjILcAHeo_D7sQ6AEIUDAF#v=onepage&q=Kadamba%20Dynasty%20brahmin&f=false|title=Indian Caste System|date=2004|publisher=Discovery Publishing House|isbn=978-81-7141-847-3|language=en}}</ref>\n# [[Pallava dynasty|Pallava Dynasty]] {c.285 -905 CE} was a Dynasty of the [[Bharadwaja|Bharadwaja Gotra]] , prayers were conducted By Brahmins, Pallavas Ruled [[Andhra Pradesh|Andhra (Krishna-Guntur)]] and [[Tamil Nadu|North]] and [[Tamil Nadu|Central Tamil Nadu]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iepJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT193|title= Encyclopedia of Monasticism|page=193|author=William M. Johnston|publisher=Routledge|accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref>\n# The [[Chalukya dynasty|Chalukyas of Badami]] were an indigenous Brahmin Family with [[Kannada]] as their mother tongue<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rao|first=M. S. Nagaraja|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=xnMtAQAAIAAJ&q=Chalukyas+of+Badami+brahmin&dq=Chalukyas+of+Badami+brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi926a8mMzoAhX56nMBHdh1DrcQ6AEIQDAD|title=The Chalukyas of Badami: seminar papers|date=1978|publisher=Mythic Society|language=en}}</ref>\n# The [[Oiniwar Dynasty]], based in [[Mithila]] were [[Maithil Brahmins]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jha|first=Ugra Nath|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=V0xmAAAAMAAJ&q=Oiniwar+Dynasty+Brahmin&dq=Oiniwar+Dynasty+Brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiXvsKXmczoAhWHyDgGHffXB_oQ6AEILjAB|title=The Genealogies and Genealogists of Mithila: A Study of the Panji and the Panjikars|date=1980|publisher=Kishor Vidya Niketan|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=yPcZAAAAIAAJ&q=Oiniwar+Dynasty+Brahmin&dq=Oiniwar+Dynasty+Brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiXvsKXmczoAhWHyDgGHffXB_oQ6AEIJzAA|title=The Eastern Anthropologist|date=1966|publisher=Ethnographic and Folk Culture Society|language=en}}</ref>\n# [[Vakataka dynasty|Vakataka Dynasty]] was a Dynasty from the Indian subcontinent that is believed to have extended from the southern edges of [[Malwa]] and [[Gujarat]] in the North to the [[Tungabhadra River]] in the South as well as from the [[Arabian Sea]] in the West to the edges of [[Chhattisgarh]] in the East<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=gE7udqBkACwC&pg=PA154&dq=Vakataka+Dynasty+Brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjMraCymczoAhX94jgGHSOnDFMQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=Vakataka%20Dynasty%20Brahmin&f=false|title=A Comprehensive History Of Ancient India (3 Vol. Set)|date=2003-12-01|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|isbn=978-81-207-2503-4|language=en}}</ref>\n# [[Varman dynasty|Varman Dynasty]] was an ancient Dynasty in [[Assam]], alongside [[Davaka]]. All the rulers of this Dynasty were [[Kamrupi Brahmins]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Dikshit|first=K. R.|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=iorHBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA23&dq=Varman+Dynasty+Brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIz_HqmczoAhX9zDgGHYI-BjcQ6AEIPjAD#v=onepage&q=Varman%20Dynasty%20Brahmin&f=false|title=North-East India: Land, People and Economy|last2=Dikshit|first2=Jutta K.|date=2013-10-21|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-94-007-7055-3|language=en}}</ref>\n# [[Brahmin dynasty|Brahman Dynasty of Sindh]] was founded By [[Chach of Aror|Chach of Alor]], later Ruled By Chandar of Sindh and [[Raja Dahir]]\n# [[Bhurshut|Bhurshut Dynasty]] was a medieval Hindu Dynasty spread across what is now Howrah and Hooghly districts in the Indian state of West Bengal;which was Ruled By a Royal Brahmin Family\n# [[Baghochia|Baghochia Dynasty]] was founded By [[Raja Bir Sen]] and were the ruling Dynasty of [[Hathwa Raj]]. The [[Cadet branch]] of the Family also Ruled [[Tamkuhi Raj]], [[Salemgarh Estate]], [[Ledo Gadi]], [[Kiajori estate]] and [[Kharna Ghatwali]].\n# [[Gupta Empire]] <ref>{{Cite book|last=Agrawal|first=Ashvini|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=hRjC5IaJ2zcC&pg=PA259&dq=THE+PARIVRAJAKA+dynasty+brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiDmJWx-cvoAhWSzTgGHSB2ADYQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=Chalukyas%20of%20Badami&f=false|title=Rise and Fall of the Imperial Guptas|date=1989|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ.|isbn=978-81-208-0592-7|language=en}}</ref>\n# [[Hindu Shahi|Kabul Shahi Dynasty]] belonged to Bali clan of [[Mohyal Brahmin]]\n# [[Aryacakravarti dynasty|Aryacakravarti Dynasty]] which was Ruled By [[Tamil Brahmin]]s\n# [[Jaffna Kingdom]] of Sri Lanka;which was Ruled By [[Tamil Brahmin]]s\n# [[Peshwas|Peshwai]] , [[Peshwa|Peshwas]] were [[Brahmin]] and were the [[De facto]] rulers of [[Maratha Empire]]\n# [[Patwardhan dynasty|Patwardhan Dynasty]] was an Indian Dynasty established By the [[Chitpavan]] [[Brahmin]] [[Patwardhan]] Family\n# [[Karkota Empire]] was founded By Durlabhvardhana  a Kashimiri Brahmin during the lifetime of [[Harshavardhan]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=Schaeffer|first=Kurtis R.|title=Tales of the Great Brahmin|date=2005-06-02|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195173734.003.0002|work=Dreaming the Great Brahmin|pages=12\u201333|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-517373-4|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Mehta|first=Jaswant Lal|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=iUk5k5AN54sC&pg=PA31&lpg=PA31&dq=brahman+shahi+afghanistan&source=bl&ots=KegrVUk93P&sig=ACfU3U19WJtCPyxkQqWJh674V9Y9wVOL4g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwio1o3W1svoAhUz4zgGHRIRBbc4ChDoATADegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=karkota&f=false|title=Advanced Study in the History of Medieval India|date=1979|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|isbn=978-81-207-0617-0|language=en}}</ref>[[File:SungaEmpireMap.jpg|thumb|246x246px|Map of [[Shunga Empire|Shung Empire]] ]][[File:Raja dahir.jpg|thumb|262x262px|Potrait of Brahman [[Raja Dahir|Maharaja Dahir Sen]] of [[Brahman dynasty of Sindh|Sindh Brahman Dynasty]]]][[File:Extent of the Maratha Empire in 1759 from Shivaji his Life and Times by Gajanan Bhaskar Mehendale.svg|thumb|274x274px|Maratha Empire Map under [[Peshwa|Peshwa Brahmins]]]][[File:Sindh 700ad.jpg|thumb|207x207px|Map Of [[Brahman dynasty of Sindh|Brahman Sahi Dynasty]] Of [[Sindh]]]][[File:Karkota Empire, India (derived).jpg|thumb|206x206px|Map of [[Karkota Empire]] under [[Kashmiri Brahmins]]]]\n# [[Utpala dynasty|Utpala Dynasty]] a [[Kashmiri Brahmin|Kashimiri Brahmin]] Dynasty after [[Karkota Empire]]  <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n# [[Lohara dynasty|Lohara Dynasty]] a [[Kashmiri Brahmin|Kashimiri Brahmin]] Dynasty after [[Utpala dynasty|Utpala Dynasty]]   <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n# [[Yasakara Dynasty]] of [[Kashmiri Brahmin|Kashmir Brahmin]] Dynasty \n# [[Aundh State]], Ruled By [[Deshastha|Deshasthas Brahmin]]s\n# [[Bhor State]], a 9 gun Salute princely state Ruled By [[Deshastha|Deshasthas Brahmin]]s\n# [[Gaurihar State]] of Madhya Pradesh Ruled By [[Deshastha|Deshasthas Brahmin]]s\n# [[Jalaun State]] of [[Bundelkhand]] region Ruled By a [[Deshastha|Deshasthas Brahmin]]s\n# [[Jhansi State]] Ruled By [[Newalkar|Newelkar House]] of [[Karhade Brahmin|Karhades Brahmins]]\n# [[Jamkhandi State]] Ruled By [[Chitpavan|Chitpavans Brahmin]]s\n# [[Ramdurg State]] Ruled By [[Chitpavan|Chitpavans Brahmin]]s\n# [[Miraj Junior]] and [[Miraj Senior]] states were Ruled By  [[Chitpavan|Chitpavans Brahmin]]s\n# [[Kurundvad Senior]] and [[Kurundvad Junior]] states were rulered By Patwardhan clan of [[Chitpavan|Chitpavans Brahmin]]s\n# [[Sangli State]], an 11 gun Salute princely state Ruled By [[Chitpavan|Chitpavans Brahmin]]s\n# [[Panth-Piploda Province]] a province of British India Ruled By a [[Deshastha|Deshasthas Brahmin]]s\n# [[Chaube Jagirs]] were a group of five feudatory princely states of Central India during the period of the British Raj. which were Ruled By different branches of Brahmin Family.\n# [[Benares State]], a 13 gun salute (15 gun salute local) state Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihar Brahmins]]\n# [[Arni jagir|Arni estate]] was a jagir in the erstwhile Madras Presidency which was Ruled By [[Deshastha|Deshasthas Brahmin]]s\n# [[Yelandur estate]] was a jagir in the erstwhile Mysore State which was Ruled By [[Madhwa Brahmins|Madhwas Brahmins]]\n# [[Baudh State]] was a princely state Ruled By a Brahmin Family who adopted as successor a nephew of the [[Raja of Keonjhar]]\n# [[Raj Darbhanga|Darbhanga Raj]] of Mithila, Bihar - Ruled By [[Maithil Brahmin|Maithil Brahmins]]\n# Singhwara Estate of Mithila, Bihar - Ruled By [[Maithil Brahmin|Maithil Brahmins]]\n# [[Rajshahi Raj]] of [[Bengal]] - Ruled By [[Rajshahi Family]] - ([[Maitra|Varendra Brahmins]])\n# [[Banaili|Banaili Estate]] of Bihar - Ruled By [[Chaudhary Bahadhur Lineage]] - ([[Maithil Brahmin|Maithil Brahmins]])\n# [[Bhawal Estate]] of [[Bengal]] - Ruled By Choudhary Lineage - ([[Shrotriya Brahmin]])\n# [[Nadia Raj]] of Bengal - Ruled By Roy or Ray Lineage - ([[Kulin Brahmin|Kulin Brahmins]])\n# [[Dighapatia Raj]] of Bengal - Ruled By Roy Lineage - ([[Maitra|Varendra Brahmins]])\n# [[Muktagacha Raj]] of Bengal - Ruled By Chowdhary Lineage - ([[Maitra|Varendra Brahmins]])<ref name=\"Banu1992p22\" />\n# [[Susanga Raj]] of Bengal - Ruled By Sinha Lineage - ([[Maitra|Varendra Brahmins]])\n# [[Vishalgad Jagir|Vishalgad Estate]] of the [[British Raj]] - Ruled By Pant Prathinidhi Family - ([[Deshastha Brahmin|Deshastha Brahmins]])\n# [[Ichalkaranji Jagir|Ichalkaranji Estate]] of the [[British Raj]] - Ruled By Joshi Family - ([[Chitpavan Brahmin|Chitpavan Brahmins]])\n# [[Yelandur estate|Yelandur Estate]] of [[Kingdom of Mysore|Mysore Kingdom]] - Ruled By [[Madhwa Brahmin]] Family.\n# [[Panyam|Panyam Zamindari]] of Madras Presidency - Ruled By [[Deshastha Brahmins]]\n# [[Arni jagir|Arni Estate]] of Madras Presidency - Ruled By [[Deshastha Brahmins]]\n# [[Bettiah Raj]] Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihar Brahmins]]\n# [[Natore Raj]] of Bengal - Ruled By Roy Lineage - ([[Maitra|Varendra Brahmin]])<ref>{{cite book|author=U. A. B. Razia Akter Banu|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XyzqATEDPSgC&pg=PA21|title=Islam in Bangladesh|publisher=E. J. Brill|year=1992|isbn=90-04-09497-0|page=21}}</ref>\n# [[Tekari Raj]] of Bihar - Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihar Brahmins]]\n# [[Anapur Estate]] of Bihar - Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihar Brahmins]]\n# [[Dharhara Estate]] Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihar Brahmins]]\n# [[Jogini Estate]] Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihar Brahmins]]\n# [[Goshi Estate]]  Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihars Brahmins]]\n# [[Sheohar Raj]] Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihars Brahmins]]\n# [[Madhubhan Raj]] Ruled By [[Maithil Brahmin|Maithili Brahmins]]\n# [[Simlapal Raj]] Ruled By [[Utkal Brahmins]]\n# [[Maksudhpur Raj]] Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihar Brahmins]]\n# [[Pahleha Raj of Gaya]]\n# [[Pakhra Raj]]\n# [[Poondoi Raj]]\n# [[Ratwara Raj]]\n# [[Nathdwarar Estate of Thikhana]], [[Udaipur]]\n# [[Ajodhya Raj (formerly Mahdauna)]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]] - Ruled By [[Sakaldwipiya|Sakaldipi Brahmin]]\n# [[Ausanganj Estate of Oudh]] - Ruled By [[Gautam Brahmins|Gautham Lineage]] \n# [[Mymensingh Raj of Bengal]] - Ruled By [[Chowdhury Lineage]] - ([[Maitra|Varendra Brahmin]])\n# [[Tajpur Raj of Uttar Pradesh]] - Ruled By [[Chaudhary lineage|Chaudhary Lineage]] - ([[Tyagi|Tyagi Brahmins]])\n# [[Zamindari/Zagirdari(350 villages)]] of Asoda(Hapud) [[Uttar Pradesh]] Ruled By [[Chaudhry lineage|Chaudhry Lineage]] - [[Tyagi|Tyagi Brahmins]]\n# [[Ratangarh, Bijnor|Zamindari of Ratangarh (Bijnore)]] Ruled By [[Taga Rao Zokha Singh|Taga Rao Zokha Singh Tyagi Atri]] - He was a former commander (or ''Rao'') of the northern branch of the  [[Maratha Confederacy|Maratha Confederate Army]], whose control ranged to the [[Tarai]] baselands of the Himalayas ,Family of [[Chaudhry lineage|Chaudhry Lineage]] - [[Tyagi|Tyagi Brahmins]]\n# [[Zamindari of Siyohara(Bijnore)]] Ruled By [[Tyagi|Tyagi Brahmins]] ([[Raja Raghuraj Singh Tyagi]])\n# [[Zamindari of Sultanpur(Saharanpur)]] [[Uttar Pradesh]] Ruled By [[Tyagi|Tyagi Brahmins]]([[Chaudhry Maharaj Singh]])\n# [[Zamindari of Gannaur(Haryana)]] Ruled By [[Tyagi|Tyagi Brahmins]] of [[Bhardwaj|Bhardwaj Clan]]\n# [[Zamidari of Nestaur(Bijnore)]] [[Uttar Pradesh]] Ruled By [[Chaudhry lineage|Chaudhry Lineage]] - [[Tyagi|Tyagi Brahmins]]([[Chaudhry Shyam Narayan Singh]])\n# [[Polavaram Zamindari]] - Ruled By [[Koccharlakota Family]] - ([[Telugu Brahmin|Telugu Brahmins]])\n# [[Lakkavaram Zamindari]] - Ruled By [[Mantripregada Family]] - ([[Telugu Brahmin|Telugu Brahmins]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Brahmins]]\n[[Category:Brahmanas]]\n", "text_old": "{{original research|date=April 2020}}\n{{princely states topics}}\n[[File:Main Gate of Darbhanga Fort.jpg|thumb|Main Gate of [[Darbhanga Fort]]|alt=|303x303px]]\n[[Brahmin|Brahman]]s occupy the highest ritual position among the four [[Varna (Hinduism)|Varnas]] of [[Hinduism]]. Since the Late Vedic period the Brahmins, who were generally classified as priests,mentor,teacher who were also [[Monarch|Rulers]], [[Zamindar]]s,[[King|Kings]],[[Warrior|Warriors]] and holders of other highest administrative posts.<ref name=\"Banu1992p22\">{{cite book |author=U. A. B. Razia Akter Banu |year=1992 |title=Islam in Bangladesh |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XyzqATEDPSgC&pg=PA22 |publisher=E. J. Brill |page=22 |isbn=90-04-09497-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Idea of Nation and Its Future in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6CElDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA219|page=219|author=Shibani Kinkar Chaube|publisher=Taylor & Francis|accessdate=26 October 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Between the Empires: Society in India 300 BCE to 400 CE|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=efaOR_-YsIcC|author=Patrick Olivelle|page=151|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>Due to their martial abilities, [[Brahmins|Brahmans]] were described as [[Martial race|'the oldest martial community']], in the past having two of the oldest regiments, the [[1st Brahmans]] and [[3rd Brahmans]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Gajendra|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=3cVMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA29&dq=brahmins+martial+class&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjn1pmV3eTmAhWWIbcAHe4KCTAQ6AEILTAC#v=onepage&q=brahmins%20martial%20class&f=false|title=The Testimonies of Indian Soldiers and the Two World Wars: Between Self and Sepoy|date=2014-01-16|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=978-1-78093-820-2|language=en}}</ref> [[Brahmin|Brahmans]] are recruited in Army because of their magnificent physique; their breeding and pride of race is reflected in their cleanliness and smartness on parade. They are fine athletes, expert wrestlers, and excel in feats of strength; and they have a high reputation for courage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiandefencereview.com/interviews/soldiers-the-rajput-and-brahman/|title=Soldiers: The Rajput and Brahman|website=Indian Defence Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==Brahmin Empires, Dynasties, Princely States and Zamidari Estates in Indian Subcontinent :==\nFollowing is the List of Brahmin Empires, Dynasties,Princely States and Zamidari Estates Ruled By Brahmins in the Indian Subcontinent :\n\n# The [[Shunga Empire]] of Magadha was established By [[Pushyamitra Shunga]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Major World Religions: From Their Origins to the Present|author=Lloyd V. J. Ridgeon|page=18|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TC9TlHTe0xUC|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2003}}</ref>\n# The [[Kanva dynasty|Kanva Dynasty]] replaced the [[Shunga Empire]] in Magadha and Ruled in the Eastern regions of India<ref>{{Cite book|last=Chaurasia|first=Radhey Shyam|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=cWmsQQ2smXIC&pg=PA132&dq=kanva+dynasty&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjb7OD4lszoAhU38XMBHQAjBgIQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=kanva%20dynasty&f=false|title=History of Ancient India: Earliest Times to 1000 A.D.|date=2002-05|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist|isbn=978-81-269-0027-5|language=en}}</ref>\n# The [[Satavahana Dynasty]] - 230bc to 250ad In present day part of [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Gujrat]], [[Maharashtra]],[[Telangana]], [[Rajasthan]],[[Northern Karnataka]] etc<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=bQjwBQAAQBAJ&pg=PR124&dq=satavahana+brahmins&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwig7Z25l8zoAhXk7HMBHao_BKsQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=satavahana%20brahmins&f=false|title=U.G.C.-NET/J.R.F./SET Itihaas (Paper-II & III)|publisher=Upkar Prakashan|isbn=978-93-5013-084-1|language=hi}}</ref>\n# [[Parivrajaka dynasty|Parivrajaka Dynasty]] Ruled parts of Central India during the 5th and 6th centuries. The kings of this Dynasty bore the title Maharaja, and probably Ruled as feudatories of the [[Gupta Empire]]. The royal Family came from a Lineage of Brahmins of [[Bharadwaja|Bharadwaj Gotra]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Goyal|first=Shankar|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=mCcwAQAAIAAJ&q=Parivrajaka+Dynasty+brahmin&dq=Parivrajaka+Dynasty+brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjLqujal8zoAhUF73MBHY2dACcQ6AEIJzAA|title=India's ancient past|date=2004-01-01|publisher=Book Enclave|language=en}}</ref>\n# [[Kadamba dynasty|Kadamba Dynasty]] (345 \u2013 525 CE) was a Dynasty that Ruled [[North Karnataka|Northern Karnataka]] and the [[Konkan]] from [[Banavasi]] in present-day [[Uttara Kannada]] district<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pruthi|first=R. K.|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=rC1bJcd-MDUC&pg=PA228&dq=Kadamba+Dynasty+brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6-OqdmMzoAhXjILcAHeo_D7sQ6AEIUDAF#v=onepage&q=Kadamba%20Dynasty%20brahmin&f=false|title=Indian Caste System|date=2004|publisher=Discovery Publishing House|isbn=978-81-7141-847-3|language=en}}</ref>\n# [[Pallava dynasty|Pallava Dynasty]] {c.285 -905 CE} was a Dynasty of the [[Bharadwaja|Bharadwaja Gotra]] , prayers were conducted By Brahmins, Pallavas Ruled [[Andhra Pradesh|Andhra (Krishna-Guntur)]] and [[Tamil Nadu|North]] and [[Tamil Nadu|Central Tamil Nadu]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iepJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT193|title= Encyclopedia of Monasticism|page=193|author=William M. Johnston|publisher=Routledge|accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref>\n# The [[Chalukya dynasty|Chalukyas of Badami]] were an indigenous Brahmin Family with [[Kannada]] as their mother tongue<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rao|first=M. S. Nagaraja|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=xnMtAQAAIAAJ&q=Chalukyas+of+Badami+brahmin&dq=Chalukyas+of+Badami+brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi926a8mMzoAhX56nMBHdh1DrcQ6AEIQDAD|title=The Chalukyas of Badami: seminar papers|date=1978|publisher=Mythic Society|language=en}}</ref>\n# The [[Oiniwar Dynasty]], based in [[Mithila]] were [[Maithil Brahmins]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jha|first=Ugra Nath|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=V0xmAAAAMAAJ&q=Oiniwar+Dynasty+Brahmin&dq=Oiniwar+Dynasty+Brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiXvsKXmczoAhWHyDgGHffXB_oQ6AEILjAB|title=The Genealogies and Genealogists of Mithila: A Study of the Panji and the Panjikars|date=1980|publisher=Kishor Vidya Niketan|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=yPcZAAAAIAAJ&q=Oiniwar+Dynasty+Brahmin&dq=Oiniwar+Dynasty+Brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiXvsKXmczoAhWHyDgGHffXB_oQ6AEIJzAA|title=The Eastern Anthropologist|date=1966|publisher=Ethnographic and Folk Culture Society|language=en}}</ref>\n# [[Vakataka dynasty|Vakataka Dynasty]] was a Dynasty from the Indian subcontinent that is believed to have extended from the southern edges of [[Malwa]] and [[Gujarat]] in the North to the [[Tungabhadra River]] in the South as well as from the [[Arabian Sea]] in the West to the edges of [[Chhattisgarh]] in the East<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=gE7udqBkACwC&pg=PA154&dq=Vakataka+Dynasty+Brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjMraCymczoAhX94jgGHSOnDFMQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=Vakataka%20Dynasty%20Brahmin&f=false|title=A Comprehensive History Of Ancient India (3 Vol. Set)|date=2003-12-01|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|isbn=978-81-207-2503-4|language=en}}</ref>\n# [[Varman dynasty|Varman Dynasty]] was an ancient Dynasty in [[Assam]], alongside [[Davaka]]. All the rulers of this Dynasty were [[Kamrupi Brahmins]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Dikshit|first=K. R.|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=iorHBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA23&dq=Varman+Dynasty+Brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIz_HqmczoAhX9zDgGHYI-BjcQ6AEIPjAD#v=onepage&q=Varman%20Dynasty%20Brahmin&f=false|title=North-East India: Land, People and Economy|last2=Dikshit|first2=Jutta K.|date=2013-10-21|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-94-007-7055-3|language=en}}</ref>\n# [[Brahmin dynasty|Brahman Dynasty of Sindh]] was founded By [[Chach of Aror|Chach of Alor]], later Ruled By Chandar of Sindh and [[Raja Dahir]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mehta|first=Vinay|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=uuq0MQEACAAJ&dq=sindh+Dynasty+Brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwixvrGQmszoAhXl4zgGHW6jALcQ6AEIJzAA|title=Echoes Among Ruins: Revisiting the Brahmin Dynasty of Ancient Sind|date=2012-08-08|publisher=Createspace Independent Pub|isbn=978-1-4782-0710-8|language=en}}</ref>\n# [[Bhurshut|Bhurshut Dynasty]] was a medieval Hindu Dynasty spread across what is now Howrah and Hooghly districts in the Indian state of West Bengal;which was Ruled By a Royal Brahmin Family\n# [[Baghochia|Baghochia Dynasty]] was founded By [[Raja Bir Sen]] and were the ruling Dynasty of [[Hathwa Raj]]. The [[Cadet branch]] of the Family also Ruled [[Tamkuhi Raj]], [[Salemgarh Estate]], [[Ledo Gadi]], [[Kiajori estate]] and [[Kharna Ghatwali]].\n# [[Gupta Empire]] <ref>{{Cite book|last=Agrawal|first=Ashvini|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=hRjC5IaJ2zcC&pg=PA259&dq=THE+PARIVRAJAKA+dynasty+brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiDmJWx-cvoAhWSzTgGHSB2ADYQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=Chalukyas%20of%20Badami&f=false|title=Rise and Fall of the Imperial Guptas|date=1989|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ.|isbn=978-81-208-0592-7|language=en}}</ref>\n# [[Hindu Shahi|Kabul Shahi Dynasty]] belonged to Bali clan of [[Mohyal Brahmin]]\n# [[Aryacakravarti dynasty|Aryacakravarti Dynasty]] which was Ruled By [[Tamil Brahmin]]s\n# [[Jaffna Kingdom]] of Sri Lanka;which was Ruled By [[Tamil Brahmin]]s\n# [[Peshwas|Peshwai]] , [[Peshwa|Peshwas]] were [[Brahmin]] and were the [[De facto]] rulers of [[Maratha Empire]]\n# [[Patwardhan dynasty|Patwardhan Dynasty]] was an Indian Dynasty established By the [[Chitpavan]] [[Brahmin]] [[Patwardhan]] Family\n# [[Karkota Empire]] was founded By Durlabhvardhana  a Kashimiri Brahmin during the lifetime of [[Harshavardhan]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=Schaeffer|first=Kurtis R.|title=Tales of the Great Brahmin|date=2005-06-02|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195173734.003.0002|work=Dreaming the Great Brahmin|pages=12\u201333|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-517373-4|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Mehta|first=Jaswant Lal|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=iUk5k5AN54sC&pg=PA31&lpg=PA31&dq=brahman+shahi+afghanistan&source=bl&ots=KegrVUk93P&sig=ACfU3U19WJtCPyxkQqWJh674V9Y9wVOL4g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwio1o3W1svoAhUz4zgGHRIRBbc4ChDoATADegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=karkota&f=false|title=Advanced Study in the History of Medieval India|date=1979|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|isbn=978-81-207-0617-0|language=en}}</ref>[[File:SungaEmpireMap.jpg|thumb|246x246px|Map of [[Shunga Empire|Shung Empire]] ]][[File:Raja dahir.jpg|thumb|262x262px|Potrait of Brahman [[Raja Dahir|Maharaja Dahir Sen]] of [[Brahman dynasty of Sindh|Sindh Brahman Dynasty]]]][[File:Extent of the Maratha Empire in 1759 from Shivaji his Life and Times by Gajanan Bhaskar Mehendale.svg|thumb|274x274px|Maratha Empire Map under [[Peshwa|Peshwa Brahmins]]]][[File:Sindh 700ad.jpg|thumb|207x207px|Map Of [[Brahman dynasty of Sindh|Brahman Sahi Dynasty]] Of [[Sindh]]]][[File:Karkota Empire, India (derived).jpg|thumb|206x206px|Map of [[Karkota Empire]] under [[Kashmiri Brahmins]]]]\n# [[Utpala dynasty|Utpala Dynasty]] a [[Kashmiri Brahmin|Kashimiri Brahmin]] Dynasty after [[Karkota Empire]]  <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n# [[Lohara dynasty|Lohara Dynasty]] a [[Kashmiri Brahmin|Kashimiri Brahmin]] Dynasty after [[Utpala dynasty|Utpala Dynasty]]   <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n# [[Yasakara Dynasty]] of [[Kashmiri Brahmin|Kashmir Brahmin]] Dynasty \n# [[Aundh State]], Ruled By [[Deshastha|Deshasthas Brahmin]]s\n# [[Bhor State]], a 9 gun Salute princely state Ruled By [[Deshastha|Deshasthas Brahmin]]s\n# [[Gaurihar State]] of Madhya Pradesh Ruled By [[Deshastha|Deshasthas Brahmin]]s\n# [[Jalaun State]] of [[Bundelkhand]] region Ruled By a [[Deshastha|Deshasthas Brahmin]]s\n# [[Jhansi State]] Ruled By [[Newalkar|Newelkar House]] of [[Karhade Brahmin|Karhades Brahmins]]\n# [[Jamkhandi State]] Ruled By [[Chitpavan|Chitpavans Brahmin]]s\n# [[Ramdurg State]] Ruled By [[Chitpavan|Chitpavans Brahmin]]s\n# [[Miraj Junior]] and [[Miraj Senior]] states were Ruled By  [[Chitpavan|Chitpavans Brahmin]]s\n# [[Kurundvad Senior]] and [[Kurundvad Junior]] states were rulered By Patwardhan clan of [[Chitpavan|Chitpavans Brahmin]]s\n# [[Sangli State]], an 11 gun Salute princely state Ruled By [[Chitpavan|Chitpavans Brahmin]]s\n# [[Panth-Piploda Province]] a province of British India Ruled By a [[Deshastha|Deshasthas Brahmin]]s\n# [[Chaube Jagirs]] were a group of five feudatory princely states of Central India during the period of the British Raj. which were Ruled By different branches of Brahmin Family.\n# [[Benares State]], a 13 gun salute (15 gun salute local) state Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihar Brahmins]]\n# [[Arni jagir|Arni estate]] was a jagir in the erstwhile Madras Presidency which was Ruled By [[Deshastha|Deshasthas Brahmin]]s\n# [[Yelandur estate]] was a jagir in the erstwhile Mysore State which was Ruled By [[Madhwa Brahmins|Madhwas Brahmins]]\n# [[Baudh State]] was a princely state Ruled By a Brahmin Family who adopted as successor a nephew of the [[Raja of Keonjhar]]\n# [[Raj Darbhanga|Darbhanga Raj]] of Mithila, Bihar - Ruled By [[Maithil Brahmin|Maithil Brahmins]]\n# Singhwara Estate of Mithila, Bihar - Ruled By [[Maithil Brahmin|Maithil Brahmins]]\n# [[Rajshahi Raj]] of [[Bengal]] - Ruled By [[Rajshahi Family]] - ([[Maitra|Varendra Brahmins]])\n# [[Banaili|Banaili Estate]] of Bihar - Ruled By [[Chaudhary Bahadhur Lineage]] - ([[Maithil Brahmin|Maithil Brahmins]])\n# [[Bhawal Estate]] of [[Bengal]] - Ruled By Choudhary Lineage - ([[Shrotriya Brahmin]])\n# [[Nadia Raj]] of Bengal - Ruled By Roy or Ray Lineage - ([[Kulin Brahmin|Kulin Brahmins]])\n# [[Dighapatia Raj]] of Bengal - Ruled By Roy Lineage - ([[Maitra|Varendra Brahmins]])\n# [[Muktagacha Raj]] of Bengal - Ruled By Chowdhary Lineage - ([[Maitra|Varendra Brahmins]])<ref name=\"Banu1992p22\" />\n# [[Susanga Raj]] of Bengal - Ruled By Sinha Lineage - ([[Maitra|Varendra Brahmins]])\n# [[Vishalgad Jagir|Vishalgad Estate]] of the [[British Raj]] - Ruled By Pant Prathinidhi Family - ([[Deshastha Brahmin|Deshastha Brahmins]])\n# [[Ichalkaranji Jagir|Ichalkaranji Estate]] of the [[British Raj]] - Ruled By Joshi Family - ([[Chitpavan Brahmin|Chitpavan Brahmins]])\n# [[Yelandur estate|Yelandur Estate]] of [[Kingdom of Mysore|Mysore Kingdom]] - Ruled By [[Madhwa Brahmin]] Family.\n# [[Panyam|Panyam Zamindari]] of Madras Presidency - Ruled By [[Deshastha Brahmins]]\n# [[Arni jagir|Arni Estate]] of Madras Presidency - Ruled By [[Deshastha Brahmins]]\n# [[Bettiah Raj]] Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihar Brahmins]]\n# [[Natore Raj]] of Bengal - Ruled By Roy Lineage - ([[Maitra|Varendra Brahmin]])<ref>{{cite book|author=U. A. B. Razia Akter Banu|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XyzqATEDPSgC&pg=PA21|title=Islam in Bangladesh|publisher=E. J. Brill|year=1992|isbn=90-04-09497-0|page=21}}</ref>\n# [[Tekari Raj]] of Bihar - Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihar Brahmins]]\n# [[Anapur Estate]] of Bihar - Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihar Brahmins]]\n# [[Dharhara Estate]] Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihar Brahmins]]\n# [[Jogini Estate]] Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihar Brahmins]]\n# [[Goshi Estate]]  Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihars Brahmins]]\n# [[Sheohar Raj]] Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihars Brahmins]]\n# [[Madhubhan Raj]] Ruled By [[Maithil Brahmin|Maithili Brahmins]]\n# [[Simlapal Raj]] Ruled By [[Utkal Brahmins]]\n# [[Maksudhpur Raj]] Ruled By [[Bhumihar Brahmin|Bhumihar Brahmins]]\n# [[Pahleha Raj of Gaya]]\n# [[Pakhra Raj]]\n# [[Poondoi Raj]]\n# [[Ratwara Raj]]\n# [[Nathdwarar Estate of Thikhana]], [[Udaipur]]\n# [[Ajodhya Raj (formerly Mahdauna)]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]] - Ruled By [[Sakaldwipiya|Sakaldipi Brahmin]]\n# [[Ausanganj Estate of Oudh]] - Ruled By [[Gautam Brahmins|Gautham Lineage]] \n# [[Mymensingh Raj of Bengal]] - Ruled By [[Chowdhury Lineage]] - ([[Maitra|Varendra Brahmin]])\n# [[Tajpur Raj of Uttar Pradesh]] - Ruled By [[Chaudhary lineage|Chaudhary Lineage]] - ([[Tyagi|Tyagi Brahmins]])\n# [[Zamindari/Zagirdari(350 villages)]] of Asoda(Hapud) [[Uttar Pradesh]] Ruled By [[Chaudhry lineage|Chaudhry Lineage]] - [[Tyagi|Tyagi Brahmins]]\n# [[Ratangarh, Bijnor|Zamindari of Ratangarh (Bijnore)]] Ruled By [[Taga Rao Zokha Singh|Taga Rao Zokha Singh Tyagi Atri]] - He was a former commander (or ''Rao'') of the northern branch of the  [[Maratha Confederacy|Maratha Confederate Army]], whose control ranged to the [[Tarai]] baselands of the Himalayas ,Family of [[Chaudhry lineage|Chaudhry Lineage]] - [[Tyagi|Tyagi Brahmins]]\n# [[Zamindari of Siyohara(Bijnore)]] Ruled By [[Tyagi|Tyagi Brahmins]] ([[Raja Raghuraj Singh Tyagi]])\n# [[Zamindari of Sultanpur(Saharanpur)]] [[Uttar Pradesh]] Ruled By [[Tyagi|Tyagi Brahmins]]([[Chaudhry Maharaj Singh]])\n# [[Zamindari of Gannaur(Haryana)]] Ruled By [[Tyagi|Tyagi Brahmins]] of [[Bhardwaj|Bhardwaj Clan]]\n# [[Zamidari of Nestaur(Bijnore)]] [[Uttar Pradesh]] Ruled By [[Chaudhry lineage|Chaudhry Lineage]] - [[Tyagi|Tyagi Brahmins]]([[Chaudhry Shyam Narayan Singh]])\n# [[Polavaram Zamindari]] - Ruled By [[Koccharlakota Family]] - ([[Telugu Brahmin|Telugu Brahmins]])\n# [[Lakkavaram Zamindari]] - Ruled By [[Mantripregada Family]] - ([[Telugu Brahmin|Telugu Brahmins]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Brahmins]]\n[[Category:Brahmanas]]\n", "name_user": "Doremon9087", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Brahmin_dynasties_and_states"}
{"title_page": "Grey butcherbird", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Grey Butcherbird\n| image = Cracticus torquatus -Brisbane -garden fence-8.jpg\n| image_caption = Two perching on a garden fence in [[Brisbane]], Australia\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/103703460/0 |title=''Cracticus torquatus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Cracticus\n| species = torquatus\n| authority = ([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1801)\n}}\n[[File:Cracticus torquartus-map.jpg|thumb|right|Map of the species' range]]\n\nThe '''grey butcherbird''' (''Cracticus torquatus'') is a widely distributed species endemic to [[Australia]]. It occurs in a range of different habitats including arid, semi-arid and temperate zones. It is found across southern Australia, but is absent from the deserts of central Australia and the monsoon tropics of northern Australia.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Kearns A., Joseph L., Toon A., Cook L. | year = 2014 | title = Australia's arid-adapted butcherbirds experienced range expansions during Piestocene glacial maxima | url = | journal = Nature Communications | volume = 5 | issue = | page = 3994 | doi = 10.1038/ncomms4994 }}</ref>  It has a characteristic \"rollicking\" [[bird vocalization|birdsong]]. It appears to be adapting well to city living, and can be encountered in the suburbs of many Australian cities including Sydney and Brisbane. The grey butcherbird preys on small vertebrates including other birds.\n\nOther birds in the same family include the [[Australian magpie]], the [[currawong]]s, [[woodswallow]]s and other members of the [[butcherbird]] genus ''Cracticus''.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe grey butcherbird was first described by the English ornithologist [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] in 1801 under the [[binomial name]] ''Lanius torquatus''.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Latham | first=John | author-link=John Latham (ornithologist) | year=1801 | title=Supplementum indicis ornithologici sive systematis ornithologiae | place=London | publisher=Leigh & Sotheby | language=Latin | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33261392 | page=xviii }}</ref>\n\nClosely related species include the [[silver-backed butcherbird]] (''Cracticus argenteus'') and the [[black-backed butcherbird]] (''Cracticus mentalis''). The silver-backed butcherbird (''Cracticus argenteus'') from [[Arnhem Land]] and northwestern Australia over to [[Port Hedland]], originally described by [[John Gould]] in 1841, was later deemed to be a subspecies of the grey butcherbird. Recently, however, it has again been re-described as a separate species. The silver-backed butcherbird has two subspecies ''C. argenteus argenteus'' and ''C. a. colletti''. The black-backed butcherbird occurs in Australia on the Cape York Peninsula and in Papua New Guinea and has two subspecies.<ref name=schodde99>{{cite book| author=Schodde, Richard| author-link=Richard Schodde| author2=Mason, I.J.| author2-link=Ian J. Mason |year=1999 |title=The Directory of Australian Birds : Passerines. A Taxonomic and Zoogeographic Atlas of the Biodiversity of Birds in Australia and its Territories |location=Collingwood, Australia |publisher= CSIRO Publishing | isbn=9780643102934}}</ref>\n\n===Subspecies===\n\nThe grey butcherbird has three subspecies:<ref name=schodde99/>\n* ''C. t. torquatus'' in south-east Australia\n* ''C. t. cinereus'' is restricted to the island of Tasmania.\n* ''C. t. leucopterus'' is widespread; its distribution stretches from the west to the east coast of Australia.\n\n== Description ==\nThe grey butcherbird is a small grey, black and white bird with a weight of 90 grams (3.2&nbsp;oz), a body length between 27\u201330&nbsp;cm (10.6-11.8&nbsp;in) and a wing span expanding 37\u201343&nbsp;cm (14.6-16.9&nbsp;in). The grey butcherbird is smaller than the Pied Butcherbird (''Cracticus nigrogularis'').<ref name= HANZAB>{{Citation | author1=Peter, John M | author2=Cowling, S. J | author3=Higgins, P. J. (Peter Jeffrey), 1959- | title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand & Antarctic birds. Volume 7, Boatbill to starlings | publication-date=2006 | publisher=Oxford University Press | isbn=978-0-19-555885-2 }}</ref>\n\nThe adult grey butcherbird has a black head, top and sides; and a white chin and throat through to the lower hindneck. The upperbody is mostly dark grey with streaks of narrow white bands that extends across the uppertail-coverts at the base of the tail. The uppertail is black with narrow white tips. The wings are grey with large areas of white and the underside of the wing is also white.<ref name= birdsbackyard>Grey butcherbird. (n.d.). Retrieved from http://www.birdsinbackyards.net/species/Cracticus-torquatus. Retrieved 5 June 2017.</ref> The tip of the beak has a slight downwards hook.<ref name=birdlife>Grey butcherbird. (n.d.). Retrieved from http://www.birdlife.org.au/bird-profile/grey-butcherbird. Retrieved 5 June 2017</ref>\n\nBoth the male and female grey butcherbirds are similar in appearance, but the female is slightly smaller in size.<ref name=\"birdsbackyard\"/>\n\nThe juvenile is slightly different from the adult, as the juvenile does not have a black head, instead the head is a dark brown with fine streaks on the forehead and ear-covers and white loral spots that meet the eyes and bill, as well as having an off-white chin and throat. The upperbody is dark brown with streaks, and the uppertail-coverts are also a dark brown and have a brownish colour at the base of the uppertail. Juvenile's beaks are completely dark grey and often the hook at the tip of the beak is not obvious. The juvenile grey butcherbird is commonly mistaken for a small kingfisher.<ref name=\"birdsbackyard\"/>\n\n== Song ==\n{{listen|filename=Butcherbird.ogg|title= Song|description=The coltish song of the Grey butcherbird.}}\nAll members of the territorial group contribute to the territorial song, a loud and rollicking song with both musical and harsh elements. The song can be sung by only one member, but more often it is sung in duet or as a group. Some duets are antiphonal where it is not obvious that two or more birds are singing. Most songs are sung with more than one phase and are sung antiphonally. These songs consist of different group members singing different phases sequentially, but sometimes there are some overlap. Some songs have been known to last up to 15 minutes. During this time, there is no vocal interaction with groups from other territories.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" />\n\n==Breeding and habitat==\nThe grey butcherbird usually breed in single territorial pairs from July to January.<ref name=\"birdsbackyard\" /> Both sexes defend their territories and nest throughout the year.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The female incubates the eggs<ref name=\"birdsbackyard\" /> while the nestlings and fledglings are fed by both parents.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The nest is a shallow, bowl-shaped made from sticks and twigs. The nest is lined with grasses and other soft fibres.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /><ref name=\"birdsbackyard\" /> Nests are normally located within 10&nbsp;m (32.8&nbsp;ft) of the ground.<ref name=\"birdsbackyard\" />\n\nThe grey butcherbird is found in a range of habitats, from eucalypt forests and woodlands, mallee and acacia shrublands, rainforests and riparian vegetation to urban areas and residential townships.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /><ref name=\"birdsbackyard\" /><ref name=\"birdlife\" /> The denser forests tend to be the favour for inland areas.<ref name=\"birdsbackyard\" />\n\n==Behaviour and diet==\nGrey butcherbirds feed on invertebrates, mainly insects; small vertebrates, including other small birds and their nestlings and lizards; and occasionally fruit and small seeds.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /><ref name=\"birdlife\" /> Uneaten food can be stored in the fork of a branch to be consumed later. Uneaten food and food that is too large to be eaten whole can also be impaled or stored for later.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /><ref name=\"birdlife\" />\n\nGrey butcherbirds sit in branches and wait for prey. Prey is captured by the grey butcherbird sally-pouncing the prey on the ground.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> Small birds and insects can be captured in flight<ref name=\"birdlife\" /> by using sally-striking.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The grey butcherbird ambushes the foraging birds while they are on the ground, usually approaching and attacking them from behind.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The grey butcherbird either feeds alone, in pairs or in small family groups.<ref name=\"birdlife\" />\n\n== Gallery ==\nVarious images of butcherbirds in different contexts:\n<gallery>\nImage:Grey butcherbird (Funnell).jpg\nImage:CracticusTorquatus.jpg\nImage:greybutcherbird.jpg\nImage:Grey Butcherbird Young Singing.JPG|Juvenile\nImage:Grey Butcherbird. Cracticus torquatus on nest (15829469162).jpg\nImage:Cracticus torquatus singing - Christopher Watson.jpg|''Cracticus torquatus'' singing\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikispecies|Cracticus torquatus}}\n* [http://ibc.lynxeds.com/species/grey-butcherbird-cracticus-torquatus Grey butcherbird videos, photos & sounds] on the Internet Bird Collection\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q974220}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:butcherbird, grey}}\n[[Category:Cracticus|grey butcherbird]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1801|grey butcherbird]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Grey Butcherbird\n| image = Cracticus torquatus -Brisbane -garden fence-8.jpg\n| image_caption = Two perching on a garden fence in [[Brisbane]], Australia\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/103703460/0 |title=''Cracticus torquatus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Cracticus\n| species = torquatus\n| authority = ([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1801)\n}}\n[[File:Cracticus torquartus-map.jpg|thumb|right|Map of the species' range]]\n\nThe '''grey butcherbird''' (''Cracticus torquatus'') is a widely distributed species endemic to [[Australia]]. It occurs in a range of different habitats including arid, semi-arid and temperate zones. It is found across southern Australia, but is absent from the deserts of central Australia and the monsoon tropics of northern Australia.<ref>Kearns, A., Joseph, L., Toon, A., & Cook, L. (2014). Australia's arid-adapted butcherbirds experienced range expansions during Piestocene glacial maxima. Nature Communications, 5, 3994. doi: 10.1038/ncomms4994</ref>  It has a characteristic \"rollicking\" [[bird vocalization|birdsong]]. It appears to be adapting well to city living, and can be encountered in the suburbs of many Australian cities including Sydney and Brisbane. The grey butcherbird preys on small vertebrates including other birds.\n\nOther birds in the same family include the [[Australian magpie]], the [[currawong]]s, [[woodswallow]]s and other members of the [[butcherbird]] genus ''Cracticus''.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe grey butcherbird was first described by the English ornithologist [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] in 1801 under the [[binomial name]] ''Lanius torquatus''.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Latham | first=John | author-link=John Latham (ornithologist) | year=1801 | title=Supplementum indicis ornithologici sive systematis ornithologiae | place=London | publisher=Leigh & Sotheby | language=Latin | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33261392 | page=xviii }}</ref>\n\nClosely related species include the [[silver-backed butcherbird]] (''Cracticus argenteus'') and the [[black-backed butcherbird]] (''Cracticus mentalis''). The silver-backed butcherbird (''Cracticus argenteus'') from [[Arnhem Land]] and northwestern Australia over to [[Port Hedland]], originally described by [[John Gould]] in 1841, was later deemed to be a subspecies of the grey butcherbird. Recently, however, it has again been re-described as a separate species. The silver-backed butcherbird has two subspecies ''C. argenteus argenteus'' and ''C. a. colletti''. The black-backed butcherbird occurs in Australia on the Cape York Peninsula and in Papua New Guinea and has two subspecies.<ref name=schodde99>{{cite book| author=Schodde, Richard| author-link=Richard Schodde| author2=Mason, I.J.| author2-link=Ian J. Mason |year=1999 |title=The Directory of Australian Birds : Passerines. A Taxonomic and Zoogeographic Atlas of the Biodiversity of Birds in Australia and its Territories |location=Collingwood, Australia |publisher= CSIRO Publishing | isbn=9780643102934}}</ref>\n\n===Subspecies===\n\nThe grey butcherbird has three subspecies:<ref name=schodde99/>\n* ''C. t. torquatus'' in south-east Australia\n* ''C. t. cinereus'' is restricted to the island of Tasmania.\n* ''C. t. leucopterus'' is widespread; its distribution stretches from the west to the east coast of Australia.\n\n== Description ==\nThe grey butcherbird is a small grey, black and white bird with a weight of 90 grams (3.2&nbsp;oz), a body length between 27\u201330&nbsp;cm (10.6-11.8&nbsp;in) and a wing span expanding 37\u201343&nbsp;cm (14.6-16.9&nbsp;in). The grey butcherbird is smaller than the Pied Butcherbird (''Cracticus nigrogularis'').<ref name= HANZAB>{{Citation | author1=Peter, John M | author2=Cowling, S. J | author3=Higgins, P. J. (Peter Jeffrey), 1959- | title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand & Antarctic birds. Volume 7, Boatbill to starlings | publication-date=2006 | publisher=Oxford University Press | isbn=978-0-19-555885-2 }}</ref>\n\nThe adult grey butcherbird has a black head, top and sides; and a white chin and throat through to the lower hindneck. The upperbody is mostly dark grey with streaks of narrow white bands that extends across the uppertail-coverts at the base of the tail. The uppertail is black with narrow white tips. The wings are grey with large areas of white and the underside of the wing is also white.<ref name= birdsbackyard>Grey butcherbird. (n.d.). Retrieved from http://www.birdsinbackyards.net/species/Cracticus-torquatus. Retrieved 5 June 2017.</ref> The tip of the beak has a slight downwards hook.<ref name=birdlife>Grey butcherbird. (n.d.). Retrieved from http://www.birdlife.org.au/bird-profile/grey-butcherbird. Retrieved 5 June 2017</ref>\n\nBoth the male and female grey butcherbirds are similar in appearance, but the female is slightly smaller in size.<ref name=\"birdsbackyard\"/>\n\nThe juvenile is slightly different from the adult, as the juvenile does not have a black head, instead the head is a dark brown with fine streaks on the forehead and ear-covers and white loral spots that meet the eyes and bill, as well as having an off-white chin and throat. The upperbody is dark brown with streaks, and the uppertail-coverts are also a dark brown and have a brownish colour at the base of the uppertail. Juvenile's beaks are completely dark grey and often the hook at the tip of the beak is not obvious. The juvenile grey butcherbird is commonly mistaken for a small kingfisher.<ref name=\"birdsbackyard\"/>\n\n== Song ==\n{{listen|filename=Butcherbird.ogg|title= Song|description=The coltish song of the Grey butcherbird.}}\nAll members of the territorial group contribute to the territorial song, a loud and rollicking song with both musical and harsh elements. The song can be sung by only one member, but more often it is sung in duet or as a group. Some duets are antiphonal where it is not obvious that two or more birds are singing. Most songs are sung with more than one phase and are sung antiphonally. These songs consist of different group members singing different phases sequentially, but sometimes there are some overlap. Some songs have been known to last up to 15 minutes. During this time, there is no vocal interaction with groups from other territories.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" />\n\n==Breeding and habitat==\nThe grey butcherbird usually breed in single territorial pairs from July to January.<ref name=\"birdsbackyard\" /> Both sexes defend their territories and nest throughout the year.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The female incubates the eggs<ref name=\"birdsbackyard\" /> while the nestlings and fledglings are fed by both parents.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The nest is a shallow, bowl-shaped made from sticks and twigs. The nest is lined with grasses and other soft fibres.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /><ref name=\"birdsbackyard\" /> Nests are normally located within 10&nbsp;m (32.8&nbsp;ft) of the ground.<ref name=\"birdsbackyard\" />\n\nThe grey butcherbird is found in a range of habitats, from eucalypt forests and woodlands, mallee and acacia shrublands, rainforests and riparian vegetation to urban areas and residential townships.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /><ref name=\"birdsbackyard\" /><ref name=\"birdlife\" /> The denser forests tend to be the favour for inland areas.<ref name=\"birdsbackyard\" />\n\n==Behaviour and diet==\nGrey butcherbirds feed on invertebrates, mainly insects; small vertebrates, including other small birds and their nestlings and lizards; and occasionally fruit and small seeds.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /><ref name=\"birdlife\" /> Uneaten food can be stored in the fork of a branch to be consumed later. Uneaten food and food that is too large to be eaten whole can also be impaled or stored for later.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /><ref name=\"birdlife\" />\n\nGrey butcherbirds sit in branches and wait for prey. Prey is captured by the grey butcherbird sally-pouncing the prey on the ground.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> Small birds and insects can be captured in flight<ref name=\"birdlife\" /> by using sally-striking.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The grey butcherbird ambushes the foraging birds while they are on the ground, usually approaching and attacking them from behind.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The grey butcherbird either feeds alone, in pairs or in small family groups.<ref name=\"birdlife\" />\n\n== Gallery ==\nVarious images of butcherbirds in different contexts:\n<gallery>\nImage:Grey butcherbird (Funnell).jpg\nImage:CracticusTorquatus.jpg\nImage:greybutcherbird.jpg\nImage:Grey Butcherbird Young Singing.JPG|Juvenile\nImage:Grey Butcherbird. Cracticus torquatus on nest (15829469162).jpg\nImage:Cracticus torquatus singing - Christopher Watson.jpg|''Cracticus torquatus'' singing\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikispecies|Cracticus torquatus}}\n* [http://ibc.lynxeds.com/species/grey-butcherbird-cracticus-torquatus Grey butcherbird videos, photos & sounds] on the Internet Bird Collection\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q974220}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:butcherbird, grey}}\n[[Category:Cracticus|grey butcherbird]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1801|grey butcherbird]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Journal cites:, templated 1 journal cites (Diberri fmt authors)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_butcherbird"}
